{In the first database concerning the Berlin, we have learned how to handle the
Berlin Endgame which arises aftre the move 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 Nf6 4.0-0
Nxe4 5.d4 Nd6 6.Bxc6 dxc6 7.dxe5 Nf5 8.Qxd8 Kxd8.  As we have seen, if Black
knows what he is doing in this endgame, it's extremely difficult for White to
pose any problems.That's the reason why White started to look for some
possible deviations from the Berlin Endgame. Despite the fact that such lines
don't promise an advantage, the arising postions and structures are complex
and tricky to handle. That's why Black should be very familiar with all the
positional and tactical subtleties in order to avoid entering a difficult
position.  First of all, we will examine White's deviations on move 6.   After
} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 {Instead of entering
the Berlin Endgame, White has at his disposal three interesting alternatives -
6.Bg5, 6.Ba4 and dxe5. These deviations are the subject of the current game.
Let's analyze them step by step.} 6. dxe5 {White tries to exploit his
advantage in the development by tactical means. His main idea consists in
developing a strong initiative against the black king which is stuck in the
centre. Nevertheless, with a precise play, Black manages to equalize rather
comfortably.  Before start dealing with the move 6.dxe5, we will take a look
at White's other possibilities.} ({Firstly, we are going to start with the move
} 6. Bg5 {This move is a rare guest in the modern chess practice. Nevertheless,
it could cause troubles to an unprepared player. White not only develops a
piece with tempo but at the same time he wants to provoke his opponent to weak
his position by f7-g6 or develop a kingside attack after exchanging the
dark-squared bishops.   Of course, Black should continue developing his pieces
by} Be7 {After} 7. Bxe7 {we are at a crossroad. Black could take either with
the knight or with the queen.} {By far the most popular recapture is} Qxe7 {
Next couple of moves are obvious.} ({For those of you who are interested in
obtaining original and less explored positions, I recommend the continuation} 
7... Nxe7 {The critical position arises after the following sequence} 8. dxe5
Nxb5 9. a4 b6 10. axb5 Bb7 {Black light-squared bishop is perfectly situated
on the long diagonal. Later on, after castling, we could proceed with Ng6
followed by Re8, thus generating pressure against the central e5-pawn. As I
have pointed out in my first database concerning the Berlin, white e5-pawn has
a huge strategical importance. Such pawn secures the spatial advantage and and
makes room for manoeuvring. That's why, in this concrete position, White will
be trying to create a kingside attack. In the endgame, however, such a pawn
could easily be transformed into a weakness.   Despite the fact that according
to my analysis, Black manages to keep the balance, the objective evaluation of
this position requires further practical tests.} 11. Qd3 {This is the most
logical move. White not only prevents Black from playing a7-a6 but at the same
time he prepares to create pressure against the d7-pawn by means of the
manoeuvre Ra4-d4. Moreover, White can already play Nbd2 without closing the
way of the queen.} ({An interesting alternative is} 11. Nc3 {Let's see how the
game might continue:} Ng6 12. Ra4 O-O 13. Rd4 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Nxe5 {Black has
managed to win a pawn but White has a compensation due to the activity of his
pieces and the pressure along the d-file.} {An interesting draw was seen in
the game Hansen, T - Ponomariov, R played in 2013. After} 15. Qb7 {Black
played the strong} c6 $1 {[%csl Rb7] Now Black could chase white queen with
his rook. For instance:} 16. f4 Rb8 17. Qxa7 Ra8 18. Qb7 Rb8 19. Qa7 Ra8 20.
Qb7 {1/2-1/2 Hansen,T-Ponomariov,R/Tromso NOR 2013/The Week in Chess 979}) {
After 11.Qd3, Black should start attacking the e5-pawn without losing a
valuable time.} 11... Ng6 12. Nbd2 O-O 13. Ra4 {This position was reached in
the game Hansen,T - Borisek, J played in 2014. Black has preferred the move 13.
..Qe7 and didn't manage to obtain a complete equality. I am convinced that
it's more logical to attack the pawn with a rook.} Re8 $5 {According to my
database, this natural move is a novelty.} 14. Re1 h6 15. Rd4 Nf8 {This
position seem to be critical for the evaluation of the move 7...Nxe7. Despite
the fact that White's spatial advantage is obvious, he couldn't create threats
on the kingside since his pieces are tied to the e5-pawn. On the other hand,
Black managed to defend his d7-pawn and is now ready to bring the a8-rook into
play by means of a7-a6. If White tries to generate some activity on the
kingside by playing moves like Rg4, then we should attack the e5-pawn by Ng6.
I think that this position is rather balanced.}) 8. Bxc6 dxc6 9. dxe5 Nf5 {We
have dealt with this pawn structure while exploring the Berlin Endgame. Here,
however, the fact that queens are not exchanged makes difference. According to
the classical positional concepts, in positions where our opponent has a
spatial advantage, we should try to exchange as much minor pieces as possible.
As we could see, Black has already managed to exchange two pairs of minor
pieces. Later on, after exchanging his unstable f5-knight by means of Nh4. he
will be left with his best piece - c8 - bishop. Such a position would be
favorable for Black since there are no suitable out-posts for white knight.
Let's see a concrete example.} 10. Qd2 O-O 11. Nc3 Nh4 12. Nxh4 Qxh4 13. f4 Bf5
{In the Berlin structures, f5 is the best square for the Black bihsop. Black
f5-bishop has multiple functions in this position:  1) stops White's kingside
pawn expansion  2) prevents White from centralizing his knight by means of Ne4
3) attacks the c2-pawn} 14. Nd1 {[%cal Gd1e3] White intends to proceed with
Ne3 followed by f4-f5. That's why we should use the fact that white knight is
temporary misplaced.} f6 $1 {This move is quite typical for positions in which
we play against a pawn on e5. Generally speaking, this move eliminates White's
spatial advantage and brings the f8-rook into play. The fact that white knight
is currently on d1 makes the f7-f6 break even more favorable for Black.} {The
game might continue} 15. exf6 Qxf6 16. Ne3 Rad8 17. Qb4 Bc8 {Black has an
excellent position. Their pieces are perfectly developed while white e3-knight
lacks stability and his f-pawn could be attacked.}) ({Another possibility for
White is} 6. Ba4 {Recently, the popularity of this continuation has grown
thanks to the efforts of GM Gadir Guseinov. By keeping the tension, White
makes more difficult the development of black pieces. The main disadvantage of
this approach is that now Black could close the position by means of} e4 {Here,
after} 7. Re1 Be7 8. Ne5 O-O 9. Nc3 Bf6 10. Bf4 {Black should go for the
d4-pawn by means of} Nf5 {The critical position arises arises after the moves}
11. Nxe4 Ncxd4 {Black has an extra pawn which is fully compensated by the
activity of white pieces. As a rule, in such type of positions, we reach the
equality by giving back the pawn in order to activate our pieces.   At this
point, White has two main options at his disposal - 12.c3 and 12.Nf6.} {A more
positional approach to the position is} 12. Nxf6+ {White simply recaptures the
sacrificed pawn and enters a position in which his dark-squared bishop will
fight against opponent's knight. This position arises after the moves} ({I
think that after} 12. c3 {White is the one who is fighting for an equality.
For instance:} Ne6 ({After the forced sequence} 12... Bxe5 13. Bxe5 Ne6 14. Qg4
Nh6 15. Qf3 f5 16. Ng3 d6 17. Bf4 Nxf4 18. Qxf4 Bd7 {White keeps some
compensation for the pawn but nothing more.}) 13. Nxd7 {And here we should go
for the complications arising after} Nxf4 14. Nexf6+ gxf6 15. Nxf8 Qxd1 16.
Raxd1 Kxf8 17. Rd8+ Kg7 18. Ree8 Nd6 19. Rg8+ Kh6 20. Bd7 (20. Bb3 Ng6 21. Ba4
(21. Bxf7 Ne7 22. Rgf8 Nc6 23. Rxd6 cxd6 24. Be6 Bxe6 25. Rxa8 Bxa2 $15) 21...
Ne7 $15) 20... Bxd7 21. Rxa8 a6 {Finally, we have reached an endgame with an
interesting material balance - two rooks for three minor pieces. At first
sight, White is better since black king doesn't feel very comfortable on h6.
Nevertheless, if we look deeper into the position, we will see that Black's
counterplay connected with Nd3 shouldn't be underestimated. The situation
seems to be balanced.}) 12... Qxf6 13. Nxd7 Bxd7 14. Bxd7 Rad8 15. Be5 Qg6 16.
Bxf5 Nxf5 17. Qf3 c6 {Maybe this is the critical position for the evaluation
of the move 6.Ba4. From a strategical point of view, in positions where there
are pawns on both wings, the bishop tends to be superior to the knight. On the
other hand, knight + queen work better than knight + bishop. Given the fact
that neither side has weaknesses, I consider the position to be roughly equal.}
{White's most natural reaction would be} 18. Rad1 {And here, I like} h5 $5 {
Black not only gains space on the kingside but at the same time he solves all
the potential problems connected with the weakness of his backrank. The game
may continue} 19. h3 Rxd1 20. Rxd1 Re8 21. Bf4 Nh4 22. Qg3 Qxg3 23. fxg3 Ng6
$11 {With an equality.}) 6... Nxb5 7. a4 {White regains the sacrificed piece
and rely on his advantage in the development. On the other hand, Black's pair
of bishops is also a long-term asset. In such positions, we should try to give
back the material in the best possible way.} Nbd4 {This is by far the most
solid continuation. Sometimes, Black tries to win a pawn by going for
variations like 7...Ne5 8.Ne5 Nd6 or 7...d6 8.e6. I think that in the
abovementionned lines, White has a lasting initiative for the pawn.} 8. Nxd4 d5
9. Nxc6 ({The alternative} 9. exd6 {doesn't cause Black serious problems. The
play may continue} Bxd6 10. Re1+ Be7 11. Nxc6 ({In our game from Gibraltar
2013, the Dutch GM Twan Burg preferred the tricky} 11. Bg5 {preventing Black
from castling short.} f6 12. Be3 {In this position, I went for the risky 12...
Ne5. I think that White keeps a slight initiative in the arising positions.
Instead, Black achieves a comfortable equality after} Nxd4 13. Bxd4 O-O $11)
11... Qxd1 12. Rxd1 bxc6 {This is the critical position for the variation with
9.exd6. In the upcoming fight, White hopes to make use of black doubled pawns.
Nevertheless, as a compensation Black has a strong pair of bishops and the
b-file. That's why the position remains balanced.  Here, White's main
continuation is} 13. Bf4 {White immediately attacks the c7-weakness. In order
to equalize, Black should know the subtle} ({The high-profile game Naiditsch -
Aronian, 2014 saw} 13. Be3 {This move doesn't change the overall evaluation of
the position. After the moves} Bf5 14. Re1 O-O-O 15. Na3 Rhe8 16. Bxa7 Bxa3 17.
Rxe8 Rxe8 18. bxa3 Re4 {was reached a complitely equal position. Later on,
Aronian managed to make use of some mistakes made by his opponent and finally
won the game.}) 13... Rb8 $1 {It's important to provoke b2-b3 before playing
the natural Bf5.} 14. b3 Bf5 {Now it's difficult for White to defend his
queenside pawns. After} 15. Na3 Bxa3 16. Rxa3 {Black could make use of the
temporary misplaced a3-rook by means of the precise} Rd8 $1 {Here, the game
ends in a forced draw after} 17. Raa1 (17. Re1+ {is answered by} Kd7 {[%csl
Rc2][%cal Gf5c2,Gh8e8]}) 17... Bxc2 18. Rdc1 Bxb3 19. Rxc6 Bxa4 20. Re1+ Kf8
21. Ra6 Rd1 22. Rxd1 Bxd1 23. Rxa7 Ke7 24. Rxc7+ Ke6 $11 {With a draw. This
position was reached in the game Lagarde - Bacrot, 2015.}) 9... bxc6 {We have
reached a typical middlegame position. White is better developed, he has
better pawn structure and enjoys a spatial advantage. Later on, he could
consider launching a kingside pawn expansion. On the other hand, Black's pair
of bishop is highliy effective in this position. Also, it's important to point
out that his pawn structure is not so bad since black centre is solid and some
counterplay could be created along the b-file. Note that in a number of
positions, the e5-pawn could become an weakness.  In this position, White's
most dangerous continuation is} 10. Qd3 {This is a multipurpose move. By
playing 10.Qd3, White  not only prevents Black from developing his bishop to
f5 but at the same time, in a suitable moment, he could play Qg3, thus
creating pressure against the g7-pawn. Another dangerous idea is connected
with the f2-f4-f5 advance. In this way White gains a lot of space on the
kingside and has chances to organize a successful attack against the
opponent's king.} Qd7 {This strange looking move has a solid positional
justification. For instance, now the move Qg3 is always well met by Qg4. At
the same time, if white decides to go for a pawn expansion by playing f2-f4,
Black has at his disposal the move Qf5 followed by natural developing moves
like Be7 and 0-0. After neutralizing White's concrete attacking ideas, Black
could try to increase the attacking potential of his bishop pair.} 11. Nd2 Be7
{This is by far the most natural move. After developing his bishop, Black is
ready to castle. Later on, he could activate his light-squared bihsop via the
long diagonal. In order to achieve that, he should play c6-c5 followed by
d5-d4. Meanwhile, we should always keep an eye on the f4-f5 advance.} ({
Another possibility is} 11... a5 {[%cal Gc8a6] This approach to the position
seem to be extremely flexible. By playing 11...a5, Black is creating the
threat 12...Ba6. At the same time, he doesn't make clear his intentions
concerning the development of the f8-bishop. Here, I provide you with a
possible line.} 12. Rd1 c5 13. Nf3 c6 14. b3 ({The pawn sacrifice} 14. e6 {
hardly promises White something} {After} fxe6 15. Re1 Bd6 16. Ne5 Qc7 17. Bf4
O-O 18. Bg3 c4 $15 {White doesn't have enough compensation for the sacrificed
pawn.}) 14... Be7 15. Bg5 Qd8 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. h3 O-O $11 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gb8b4]
We have reached an approximately equal position. Black's pawn structure is
little bit spoiled and he parted with his bishop pair. Nevertheless, black
central pawns control all the important squares and his c8-bishop is quite an
active piece. Moreover, the central e5-pawn is rather weak and requires a
permanent defense. Later on, Black could consider playing Rb8 followed by Rb4.}
) 12. Nf3 {This is a solid positional move. White intends to exchange the
dark-squared bishops by means of Bg5.  After the exchange of the bishops, he
intends to organize a kingside attack by using strong combination Queen +
Knight. Of course, we shouldn't underestimate the attacking ideas connected
with the f2-f4-f5 advance.} ({Nevertheless, the strongest continuation seems
to be} 12. f4 {[%cal Gf4f5] The threat of f4-f5 obliges Black to seek for a
fast counterplay.} a5 {[%cal Gc8a6]} 13. Qc3 d4 14. Qd3 Qd5 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6]
By centralizing his queen, Black renews the threat of Ba6.} 15. b3 g6 $1 {
[%cal Gc8f5] This is a multipurpose move. Black not only stops the dangerous
f4-f5 advance but at the same time he is planning to transfer his bishop to
the perfect f5-square.} {After} 16. Re1 O-O 17. Ne4 Bf5 {White has at his
disposal the following attacking idea} 18. g4 Bxg4 19. Ba3 $1 {[%csl Rd5,Rg8]
It seems that Black is losing material since the f6-square becomes extremely
weak after the exchange of the dark-squared bishops. However, Black's
resources prove to be more than enough.} f5 ({The exchange sacrifice seems to
be a serious alternative. For instance, after the forced sequence} 19... Bh4
20. Bxf8 Rxf8 21. Nf6+ Bxf6 22. exf6 Bf5 {Black's compensation is out of
question. White has a weakened king and a spoiled pawn structure. Nevertheless,
the position remains balanced.}) 20. Bxe7 fxe4 21. Qxe4 Rf7 22. Bg5 Re8 {This
position arised in the game Kryvoruchko,Y - Bogdanovic,S, 2014. I think that
Black is already slightly better since the e5-pawn is safely blocked while
white queenside pawns could be easily attacked.}) 12... O-O 13. Bg5 {White
continues with the exectution of his plan. Now Black should decide whether to
take on g5 or make some useful developing move. In the game I have decided to
go for the second choice.} Re8 {As the reader already knows, in this pawn
structure, we prevent our opponent from creating a kingside attack by
attacking the e5-pawn. White pieces must be permanently occupied with the
defense of the central pawn.} ({Despite the abovementionned considerations, an
easier equality could have been achieved by means of the immediate exchange.
After} 13... Bxg5 14. Nxg5 {Black is just in time to exchange the queens.} Qf5
15. Nf3 {It's understadable that White waits for his opponent to exchange the
queens. Later on, he is planning to create some pressure along the c-file.
Black, however, manages to hold the balance by creating a counterplay along
the b-file.} Qxd3 16. cxd3 Bd7 17. Nd4 {Now White has two main positional
ideas - Rfc1 and Nb3-c5. That's why Black should play very energetically.} Rfb8
$1 18. Rfc1 Rxb2 19. Nxc6 Re8 20. f4 f6 {Thanks to his active pieces Black has
more than enough counterplay.}) 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. b3 {This nice prophylactical
move is designed to discourage Black from creating an active play along the
b-file. For now, White delays the decision concerning the development of his
rooks.} ({An alternative is} 15. Rfe1 {[%cal Gh2h3,Ga1d1] This move is quite
logical from a positional point of view. Ideally, White wants to play 16.h3
followed by Rad1 and start concrete action in the centre and on the kingside.
In this line of thoughts, a logical attempt would be Nd4 followed by f2-f4-f5.
In case of 15.h3, Black could reply with 15...g6 followed by Bf5 and
eventually Be4. After the text move, however, 15...g6 is well met by Nd4.} Bg4
$1 {Black immediately starts concrete actions. In case of necessity, he is
ready to exchange his bishop for the knight, thus reducing White's attacking
chances.  After the following forced sequence} 16. Nd4 c5 17. Nc6 Qd7 18. Qb5
Re6 19. Na5 Qxb5 20. axb5 Rb6 {we reach an endgame where Black equalizes
without any problems. For instance:} 21. Nc6 d4 22. Rxa7 (22. c4 dxc3 23. bxc3
Rxb5 24. c4 $11) 22... Rxa7 23. Nxa7 g5 24. b4 (24. c4 Bd7 25. f3 Rb8 26. Kf2
Ra8 27. Ra1 Re8 $11) 24... Rb7 25. Nc6 Rxb5 26. bxc5 Rxc5 27. Nxd4 Rc4 $11 {
Black regains his pawn and the position is complitely equal.}) 15... Bg4 16.
Rae1 {This is a strong positional idea. After protecting his central pawn,
White is ready to proceed with his plan by playing 17.Nd4 followed by f2-f4.
Since white knight could become extremely dangerous, we should exchange it
immediately.} Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Qc5 18. Re2 Re6 19. h3 Rae8 {This is the right
approach to the position. Now white heavy pieces will be tied to the e5-pawn.
Later on, we could eliminate White's space advantage by playing f7-f6. Here,
the transposition into an equal queen's endgame is always in the air. That's
what happend in my game.} 20. Qg3 (20. Rfe1 d4) 20... g6 21. Rfe1 f6 22. exf6
Rxe2 23. f7+ Kxf7 24. Rxe2 Rxe2 25. Qf3+ Ke7 26. Qxe2+ Kd7 27. g3 Qc3 {At this
point, I offered a draw which was accepted.} 1/2-1/2

