{This game features an important deviation that White can choose on the 5th
move - 5.Re1. This continuation became higly popular recently. In this
variation White can go for a calm position and play without risks or sacrifice
a pawn for an initiative.  In my analysis, I prove that Black keeps a
promising position in both cases.  Let's take a look at the high-level game
Najer, E - Bacrot played in 2012.  The critical position arises after the moves
} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 {We have
reached a position with a symmetrical pawn structure. White's hopes for an
advantage are connected with the misplaced d6-knight which makes difficult for
Black to develop his queenside. Nevertheless, since White hadn't completed his
development too, Black has enough time to establish coordination between his
forces.  At this point, White has two main continuations - 7.Bd3 and 7.Bf1.} 7.
Bf1 {This is by far the most popular move. Now White is ready to gain space in
the centre by means of the advance d2-d4.} ({The strange looking move} 7. Bd3 {
doesn't promise White an advantage. Nevertheless, some precision is still
required from Black. The main line goes} Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5]
By developing his knight, White is threatening to play 10.Nd5. Given the fact
that Black's knight is on d6, d5-square is very important in this variation.
Black wants to play Ne8 and d7-d5 as soon as possible, but now he is obliged
to spend one more tempo in order to prevent White from playing Nd5. Later on,
White is planning to proceed with b2-b3 followed by Bb2, thus creating a
bishop pressure against black kingside. White's ideal set-up includes also the
moves Qf3 and Rae1. If he manages to execute all these moves, he will be able
to combine the control over the e-file with the creating of dangerous threats
against black king. Of course, this scenario is almost never seen in practice.}
c6 $1 {[%cal Gd6e8,Gd7d5] This is an important move in Black's strategy. He
takes the control over the important d5-squares and prepares Ne8 followed by
d7-d5.  Here, White's most natural move is} 10. b3 ({An interesting
alternative for White is the move} 10. Re1 {This tricky idea was used by the
Cuban GM Lenier Dominguez in his game against Radjabov played in 2015. White's
idea is to meet} Ne8 {by} 11. Qe2 {Now after} Bf6 {White he makes use of the
fact that Black hasn't played d7-d5 yet and goes for} 12. Ne4 {obtaining a
pair of bishops. The critical position arises after the moves} d5 13. Nxf6+
Nxf6 14. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] Both sides achieved what they wanted. White obtained
the bishop pair while Black managed to strengthen his position in the centre.
In order to evaluate this position correctly, we should make an important
consideration. According to the classical positional principles, the bishop
pair is not that threatening in positions with a symmetrical pawn structure.
This idea could be explained by the fact that in symmetrical positions, the
number of possible pawn contacts is limited. Therefore, it's more difficult to
increase the potential of the bishops.   In the abovementioned game, Radjobov
played} Re8 15. Qf1 Ne4 {And here, after} 16. f3 {instead of the creative 16...
Re6, he could have gone for the simplest} Nc5 17. Rxe8+ Qxe8 18. Bb2 Nxd3 19.
Qxd3 f6 $11 {Equalizing on the spot.}) 10... Ne8 11. Bb2 d5 {Black has managed
to improve his position. Now he controls the important e-square and his
queenside bishop participates in the fight. At this point, Black should decide
whether to transfer his bishop to f6 or d6. In this kind of positions I prefer
to put my dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal in order to neutralize
White's b2-bishop.} 12. Qf3 {This is by far the most popular move. White
intends to double his rooks along the e-file. Later on, he could consider
transferring his knight to the kingside by means of the manoeuvre Nd1-e3.} ({
The move} 12. Qh5 {is designed to prevent Black from putting his bishop on the
long diagonal. Nevertheless, Black has no problems in establishing
coordination between his forces since White looses a valuable time. The play
may continue} Nf6 13. Qh4 Bd6 14. Re2 h6 15. Rae1 Be6 {And here, after} 16. Nd1
{, I recommend} Nd7 {This move equalizes on the spot. For instance, the natural
} 17. Qh5 {is well met by} Qg5 {Black has managed to solve all his opening
problems. After the forced exchange of the queens, White should reckon with
the threat of Nc5.}) 12... Bf6 $1 13. Re2 Nc7 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc7e6,Ge6d4]
The threat of Ne6-d4 become quite realistic. White has two main ways to deal
with it. However, neither of them gives any chances for an advantage.} {
White's attempt to spoil the coordination in Black's camp by playing} 14. Ba3 {
doesn't work very well. The game Gonzalez - Postny, 2012 saw} ({In the game
Maximov - Laznicka, 2009, White went for a complitely equal position arising
after} 14. Na4 Bxb2 15. Nxb2 Qh4 $1 16. Qg3 Qxg3 17. hxg3 Re8 {This position
is rather drawish since all the rooks will be exchanged along the e-file. The
draw is inevitable.}) 14... Re8 15. Rae1 {And now the Israeli GM opted for the
precise} Re6 $1 {It's not clear how White could further improve his position.
If he tries to bring his knight into play by} 16. Re3 {[%cal Gc3e2] Black has
at his disposal the strong} Bg5 $1 17. Rxe6 Nxe6 {Black's position is already
preferrable.}) 7... Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 10. Re1 Re8 {We have reached
the main crossroad. Black is gradually neutralizing White's slight initiative.
After the eventual exchange of the rooks, he is ready to proceed with Nf5
followed by d7-d5. Later on, he could even consider a possible exchange of the
dark-squared bishops via g5-square (normally, black f6-bishop is restricted by
the c3-d4 pawn chain).  If White wants to achieve something out of the opening,
he should play very energetically.} 11. Bf4 {This is White's most aggressive
approach. Now Black should prevent his opponent from playing Bxd6, thus
spoiling his pawn structure.} ({In our game from 2007, Kasimdzhanov gave
preference to the slow} 11. c3 {After the moves} Rxe1 12. Qxe1 Qe7 13. Qd1 Nf5
14. Bf4 d5 15. Nd2 {I was just in time to execute the desirable exchange of
the dark-squared bishops.} Bg5 {The game continued} 16. Bxg5 Qxg5 17. Nf3 Qf6
18. Qb3 c6 19. Re1 Nd6 {With a compltely equal position.}) {After 11.Bf4,
Black is forced to play} 11... Rxe1 12. Qxe1 Ne8 13. Nc3 {White's hopes of an
advantage are connected with this pawn sacrifice. The knight is heading to the
key d5-square.} Bxd4 14. Nd5 d6 {This is the most solid continuation which I
recommend.} ({Interesting positions could arise after} 14... c6 15. Ne7+ Kf8
16. Nxc8 Qf6 {At first sight, it seems that Black is in trouble. His king is
unsafe, he is a piece down and it's White to move. Nevertheless, the
tournament practice shows that Black holds this position.   If we look a
little bit deeper, it becomes clear that since Bf4 and Nc8 are under attack,
Black regains the piece. Moreover, his king is not in an immediate danger
because White could create direct threats.  Also, we should take into
consideration the fact that, in a suitable moment, Black could take one more
pawn by means of Bxb2.} 17. Qb4+ {The idea behind this tricky continuation is
to weaken Black's pawn structure before giving back the piece.} ({Another
decent continuation is} 17. Rd1 Rxc8 18. Qe4 {and now Black should probably go
for the ending arising after} Bxf2+ 19. Kxf2 g5 20. Rxd7 Rc7 21. Rxc7 Nxc7 22.
Qe5 Qxf4+ 23. Qxf4 gxf4 24. Bd3 h6 25. Kf3 $14 {Despite the fact that White
keeps some advantage, Black has excellent drawing chances. Of course, such an
ending is not everybody's cup of tea.}) 17... c5 18. Qd2 Rxc8 19. c3 Be5 20.
Bxe5 Qxe5 21. Qxd7 Qc7 22. Rd1 Qxd7 23. Rxd7 Rc7 24. Rxc7 Nxc7 {[%cal Gf8e7,
Gc7e8,Ge8d6,Ge7f6,Gf6e5] This position is objectively equal. Black should put
his knight on d6 (controlling the important e4 and c4 squares) and centralize
his king. 1/2 (34)-1/2 Kasimdzhanov,R-Leko,P/London ENG 2012}) 15. Bg5 {This
move is forced. Otherwise, Black will just follow up with 15...Be6. The
following sequence looks pretty much forced.} Bf6 {This is Black's most
popular choice. Despite the fact that Black accepts a slightly inferior pawn
structure, he tries to exchange pieces and enter an an ending where his extra
pawn will be an important factor.} ({Even though 15...Bf6 is Black's most
popular choice in this position, I believe that he has an easier way to the
equality} 15... f6 {At first sight, this approach is quite risky since black
weakens the a2-g8 diagonal. However, there is no a forced way in which White
could exploit that weakness. For example, after} 16. Bc4 (16. Be3 Bxb2 17. Rb1
c6) 16... Kh8 {Black just removes his king from the dangerous diagonal. The
game may continue} 17. Qe4 fxg5 18. Bd3 {And here, Black has an original
solution at his disposal} Bf5 $1 19. Qxf5 Nf6 $1 {This is the point! After
exchanging the knights, Black has no problems at all.} 20. c3 (20. Nxf6 g6)
20... g6 21. Qxg5 Bxf2+ 22. Kh1 Nxd5 23. Qxd5 Qe7 24. Qxb7 Rf8 {With an equal
position.}) 16. Nxf6+ Nxf6 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. Bd3 {Maybe this natural move is
not White's most precise continuation. White's main idea must be to prevent
Black from finishing his development by means of f6-f5, Be6 and Qf6.} ({In his
game against Kramnik from 2012, the British GM Luke Mc Shane preferred} 18. Qe4
{[%csl Rb7,Rc8][%cal Ge4b7,Gc8b7] Now black c8-bishop is tied to the b7-pawn.
After} f5 {White should follow up with the precise} 19. Qf3 $1 {[%csl Rb7]
[%cal Ga1e1,Gf3b7] Black keeps the pressure against the b7-pawn and at the
same time intends to bring his rook into play via e1-square. If Black want's
to cover the e-file by means of} ({In this position, Mc Shane played} 19. Qe3 {
allowing his opponent to develop his bishop.} Be6 {After} 20. Qg3+ Kf8 21. Qc3
Ke7 $1 22. Re1 Kd7 23. Bc4 Qh8 24. Bxe6+ fxe6 25. Qb3 Re8 {was reached an
extremely interesting endgame. Black has managed to fix his pawn structure and
parry White's direct threats. Generally speaking, the position is balanced,
but every single move is very important.}) 19... Qe7 {the White could make use
of the following subtlety} ({After} 19... Be6 20. Qxb7 Rb8 21. Qxa7 Rxb2 22. a4
Rxc2 23. a5 {White is better thanks to his outside passed pawn on a5.}) 20.
Qg3+ Kh8 21. Qc3+ Kg8 22. Re1 {White rook has finally entered the play. After}
Be6 23. Re3 {[%cal Ge3g3]} f4 24. Re4 {White's chances are somewhat preferable
since Black king is weakened.}) 18... f5 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gd8f6] Black is planning
to stabilize his position by means of 19...Be6 followed by Qf6. He hopes that
his extra pawn will start telling in a long-term.} 19. Qe3 Be6 {Now White
regains the sacrificed pawn after} 20. Qf3 c6 21. Bxf5 Bxf5 22. Qxf5 {We have
reached a position with an equal material. In the future, White will be trying
to exploit the weakened position of black king. However, it will be a
difficult task since the material is quite reduced. Also, we shouldn't
underestimate the fact that it's Black to move now.} Qe7 $1 {It's important to
take the control over the open e-file. According to one of the basic
positional rules, it's impossible to create a successful attack in positions
where your opponent controls the only open file. Nevertheless, some accuracy
is still required from Black.} 23. Qg4+ ({More to the point was} 23. Rd1 {when
Black should proceed with} Re8 24. g3 Qe6 {It turns out that White couldn't
prevent the exchange of the queens. For instance} 25. Qg5+ Qg6 26. Qd2 ({After
} 26. Qxg6+ hxg6 27. Rxd6 Re1+ 28. Kg2 Rb1 29. b3 Rb2 {We reach a drawn ending.
}) 26... Re6 27. c4 Qe4 28. b3 h6 {The position is equal. White couldn't make
further progress.}) 23... Kf8 24. Qd4 f6 $6 {This move is rather dubious since
it weakens the kingside. Black should have preferred} (24... Qe5 $1 {which
leads to an equality after} 25. Qb4 (25. Qxe5 dxe5 26. Rd1 Ke7 $11) 25... Re8
26. h3 Re7 27. Rd1 d5 28. b3 b6 $11) 25. g3 d5 26. Rd1 Re8 27. Qxa7 (27. c4
dxc4 28. Qxc4 Rd8 29. Rxd8+ Qxd8 30. Qc5+ Kg7 31. Qxa7 Qd1+ 32. Kg2 Qd5+ 33. f3
c5 34. Qa5 b6 $1 $11) 27... Qb4 ({Even in case of} 27... Qe2 {White keeps the
advantage. For example} 28. Qc5+ Kf7 29. Rd3 Re4 30. b3 h5 31. Kg2 $14 h4 32.
h3 hxg3 33. Rxg3 Re7 (33... Rf4 34. Qe3 Qxe3 35. Rxe3 Rh4) 34. a4 {White is a
pawn up and has serious winning chances.}) 28. Qd4 Qxd4 29. Rxd4 Re2 30. Rb4 b5
31. c3 $16 h5 32. Kg2 Kf7 33. Kf3 Re1 34. a4 bxa4 35. Rxa4 Ke6 36. h4 Rb1 37.
Rb4 c5 38. Rb8 c4 39. Rb4 Ke5 40. Rb8 Kf5 41. Ke3 Ke5 42. Rb7 Re1+ 43. Kf3 Rb1
44. g4 hxg4+ 45. Kxg4 Rg1+ 46. Kf3 Rh1 47. Rh7 Rb1 48. h5 Rxb2 49. h6 Rb1 50.
Re7+ Kd6 51. Re8 Rh1 52. Rh8 Ke5 53. h7 Kf5 54. Rd8 Rxh7 55. Rxd5+ Ke6 56. Rc5
Rh3+ 57. Ke4 Rxc3 58. Rc6+ Kf7 59. Kd4 Rf3 60. Rxc4 Rxf2 61. Ke3 Ra2 62. Kf4
Kg6 63. Rb4 Ra1 64. Rb5 Rh1 65. Kg4 f5+ 66. Kf4 Rf1+ 67. Kg3 Kg5 68. Rb8 Rg1+
69. Kf3 Rf1+ 1/2-1/2

