{After covering the ways in which White could deviate from the Berlin endgame
on his 5th and 6th move, we should start dealing with the most popular
deviation nowadays - 4.d3. Despite the fact that this move is almost always
connected with an exchange on c6 on the next move, White has the option to
combine it with 5.Nc3 or 5.c3.   The current game features the move 5.Nc3. The
fact that this idea was used by the World Champion Magnus Carlsen makes it
important.   I would like to provide you with my comments to the game Carlsen,
M - Anand,V in which Black managed to equalize rather in a flawless manner.} 1.
e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 {Since White experience difficulties to
obtain an advantage in the Berlin endgame, we could say that 4.d3 is the new
main line. This is a rather flexible approach to the position. With his last
move White protects his e4-pawn and threatens to win a pawn by playing 5.Bxc6
followed by Nxe5.} Bc5 {Black defends the pawn in a tactical way. Now White
couldn't take the pawn because after 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.Nxe5 since Black is winning
after 6...Qd4.  Of course, the alternative 4...d6 is playable too.
Nevertheless, I find it a little bit passive. Generally, in this kind of
positions, I would like to play d7-d6 only when my dark-squared bishop had
already occupied an active position.} 5. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3a4] The idea behind
this move is to play Nc3-a4 in response to d7-d6. By exchanging the strong
c5-bishop, White obtains a bishop pair. It's important to point out that in
such kind of positions, the bishop pair could be rather dangerous since White
has a variety of pawn contacts at his disposal. Generally speaking, his plan
includes a quite development of the pieces followed by d3-d4 in a suitable
moment. Normally, his light-squared bishop is being transfered to c2 via a4.}
d6 6. Na4 Bb6 7. Nxb6 axb6 8. c3 {White managed to execute his main idea. On
the other hand, as a compensation, Black has the a-file at his disposal. It's
important to understand that Black's biggest problem in such kind of positions
is his c6-knight. As I have already mentionned in my comments to 5.Re1
variation, from c6-squares, the knight not only obstructs the development of
our queenside pieces but at the same time the c-pawn couldn't participate in
the fight for the centre. That's why in this structure, after castling, Black
should fo for the typical manoeuvre Ne7-g6. Later on, Black could fight for
the centre by means of c7-c6 followed by d6-d5. Also, we should take into
consideration the fact that the g6-knight protects the e5-pawn and could
participate in some active actions on the kingside.} Bd7 {[%cal Gc6e7,Ge7g6]
By eliminating the pin along the a4-e8 diagonal, Anand immediately prepares
the manoeuvre Ne7-g6.} ({In my game against Atakisi played in 2005, I gave
preference to} 8... O-O {The knight transfer to the kingside was executed
after the moves} 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 Bd7 11. O-O Ne7 $1 {Just in time! White
couldn't spoil our kingside pawn structure because of the unprotected position
of the b5-bishop. Once we manage to exchange the light-squared bishops, our
problems are over and we are ready to overtake the initiative on the kingside.}
12. Bxd7 Nxd7 13. Bxe7 {I think that this exchange is pretty logical.
Otherwise, in some position Black could proceed with g7-g5 after which white
bishop will be out of play.} ({For example} 13. d4 Re8 14. Re1 g5 15. Bg3 Ng6 {
[%csl Rg3] Black gaind a lot of space on the kingside while White has
difficulties to bring his bishop into play.}) 13... Qxe7 14. Re1 Qe6 15. a3 f5
{[%cal Gf8f7,Ga8f8] Black managed to comfortably equalize and now overtakes
the initiative. Later on, he could consider doubling his rooks along the
f-file. 0-1 (79) Atakisi,U-Georgiev,K/Svilengrad 2005/CBM 107 ext}) 9. Ba4 Ne7
10. Bc2 Ng6 11. h3 {This is generally a useful prophylactic move. In such kind
of positions, the pin along the d1-h5 diagonal could be very annoying.} O-O 12.
O-O h6 {This move is very similar to White's 11.h3. When we have a knight on
g6, however, the pin is not that threatening since after h7-h6, white bishop
couldn't go back to h4.} 13. Re1 Re8 {[%cal Gd7c6] This is an important
positional move. In his outstanding book "My System", the remarkable old
master Aaron Nimzowitsch introduces the so-called mysterious rook moves. Such
moves refer to situations in which we place a rook behind our own pawn with a
prophylactical idea. In this concrete position, by placing his rook on e8,
Black creates an indirect pressure against the e4-pawn.   Anand's strategy
becomes much more clear on the next move. In response to} 14. d4 {he played}
Bc6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf6e4,Gc6e4,Ge8e4] Black managed to creat an indirect
pressure against the e4-pawn. In this way, he forces White to clarify the
situation in the centre. For instance, in case of 15.d5 Bd7, the closed centre
gives Black a chance to organize a kingside attack. He could continue with
moves like Nh5-f4 followed by Qf6, creating threats on the kingside. In such
cases, the h3-pawn is vulnerable.} ({An interesting alternative is} 14... Qc8 {
Black avoids the exchange of the queens and is planning to organize a kingside
attack.. In a suitable moment, some tactics connected with Bxh3 are working
very well.   The game might continue} 15. a3 b5 16. Be3 exd4 (16... Bc6 17. Nd2
) 17. Nxd4 Ne5 {with an approximately equal position.}) 15. dxe5 dxe5 {It's
obvious that the exchnage of the central pawns is highly favorable for Black.
White has lost his spatial advantage while his bishop pair is not quite
effective in symmetrical positions. Moreover, black f6-knight could be
trasferred to the suitable c5-square.} 16. Qxd8 Rexd8 $1 {This is a right
decision. Now both black rooks are very active. At this point, Anand is ready
to bring his knight to c5. We can draw the conclusion that Black has a
comfortable equality.} 17. g3 {This move is necessary. White must restrict the
activity of black g6-knight.} Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5]} 18. Be3 Nc5 {Anand
demonstrates an excellent positional understanding. From c5, his knight not
only attacks the e4-pawn, but at the same time participates in the fight for
the weak d3-square. For example, in some moment, Black could proceed with the
manoeuvre Bb5-d3.} 19. Nd2 (19. Bxc5 bxc5 20. a3 f6 21. Rad1 $11) 19... Nf8 {
[%cal Gf8e6] Another useful move. Anand brings his second knight into play.
Now he is intending to follow with Nfe6.} 20. f3 Nfe6 21. h4 Bb5 22. a3 Rd7 {
Once White played a2-a3, Black rook has no work on the a-file. That's why
Black wants to double his rooks along the d-file.} ({Nevertheless, I would
have preferred} 22... Na4 23. Ra2 Rd6 $15 {[%cal Ga8d8] followed by Rad8. In
this position, white pieces seem to be too passive. It's already Black who is
fighting for an advantage here.}) 23. b4 Nd3 24. Reb1 Ba4 $1 {After exchanging
the light-squared bishops, Black will be able to make use of the weakened
complex of light squares on the queenside.} 25. Bxa4 Rxa4 26. Kf1 b5 27. Ke2
Ra6 28. h5 c5 $6 {This pawn sacrifice is a mistake which allows White to
obtain an advantage.} ({An interesting option would have been} 28... g6 $1 {
Black eliminates White's spatial advantage on the kingside.} 29. hxg6 fxg6 {
[%cal Gh6h5,Ga6d6,Gh5h4,Gg6g5] Later on, after doubling his rooks on the
d-file, Black could try to weaken the f4-square by means of h6-h5-h4.} 30. Rb3
{[%csl Rd3][%cal Gc3c4] White is planning to use the vulnerable d3-knight by
playing c3-c4.} Rad6 31. Kf1 {In this position, Black has a beautiful resource
which leads to a forced draw.} Ndf4 $3 {This is the point. The game may
continue} 32. gxf4 exf4 33. Bd4 Nxd4 34. cxd4 Rxd4 35. Nb1 Rd1+ 36. Kg2 Re1 37.
Ra2 Rdd1 38. Nc3 Rg1+ 39. Kf2 Rgf1+ 40. Kg2 Rg1+ {With a prepetual.}) 29. bxc5
Ndxc5 30. Rxb5 Na4 31. Rc1 Rc7 32. Nb1 f6 33. c4 b6 34. Rd5 Nac5 35. Rc2 Rc6
36. Rb2 Kh7 37. Rb4 g6 38. hxg6+ Kxg6 39. Rd2 h5 40. Nc3 Rxa3 41. Nd5 Kf7 42.
Nxb6 Nb3 43. Rd7+ Ke8 44. Rb7 Nbd4+ 45. Bxd4 Nxd4+ 46. Kd1 Kd8 47. Rd7+ Ke8 48.
Rb7 Kd8 49. Nd5 Ra1+ 50. Kd2 Ra2+ 51. Rb2 Rxb2+ 52. Rxb2 Nxf3+ 53. Kd3 Ng5 54.
Rb8+ Kd7 55. Rb7+ Kd6 56. Nxf6 Ra6 57. Ne8+ Kc5 58. Rc7+ Kb4 59. Rb7+ Kc5 60.
Rc7+ Kb4 61. Rb7+ 1/2-1/2

