{Recently, a lot of top players began to combine the move 4.d3 with 5.0-0
followed by 6.c3. The fact that this line was played at the FIDE Candidates
2016 by players like Anand and Caruana shows that this approach should be
taken seriously.   In our first game concerning this move order, Anand makes
an attempt to improve on the main line. According to my analysis, Topalov
reacts correctly and manages to solve his opening problems. Later on, after a
lot of missed opportunities, he loses the game.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
4. d3 Bc5 5. O-O d6 6. c3 {White is playing in an Italian style. The fact that
his bishop is on b5 (instead of c4) helps him to put a stronger pressure on
Black's centre. Of course, in such kind of positions, White's main idea
consists in gaining space in the centre by means of d3-d4.} O-O 7. Nbd2 {This
is by far White's most popular continuation in this position. Now the e4-pawn
is protected and White could consider the advance d3-d4 under favorable
circumstances. Of course, he could gradually prepare the central pawn advance
by playing h2-h3, Re1, Nf1-g3 and only then d3-d4. It's important to point out
that in some cases, white knight goes to c4, thus creating a pressure against
black centre.   Before start dealing with 7.Nbd2, we should pay attention to
White's alternatives on move 7.} ({The direct} 7. d4 {tends to be premature.
After the precise} Bb6 {, it turns out that White has problems to hold his
centre without giving his light-squared bishop. In her game against Anand
played in 2006, Judith Polgar played} 8. Qd3 ({Of course, in case of} 8. Bxc6
bxc6 9. dxe5 {Black simply grabs the pawn} Nxe4 {[%csl Gb6,Gc8] entering a
position where his bishop pair is powerful.}) ({As the reader know from my
comments to the game Carlsen - Anand, the move} 8. d5 {is a serious positional
concession. This consideration is even more valid in positions in which black
dark-squared bishop had already occupied the a7-g1 - diagonal. Now Black has a
free hand to start an active operations on the kingside. Here, he could follow
with} Ne7 {[%cal Gh7h6,Ge7g6,Gf6h5,Gd8f6,Gh5f4] One of the plans allowing us
to develop an initiative on the kingside includes the moves h7-h6, Ng6, Nh5
followed by Qf6 and Nhf4.}) ({White central pawns remain vulnerable even after
the natural} 8. Re1 {In such kind of positions, the possibility to create a
pin along the h5-d1 diagonal allows us to strengthen our pressure. After} exd4
9. cxd4 Bg4 {[%csl Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc6d4,Gb6d4,Gf6e4] In order to defend his
pawns White is forced to part with his pair of bishops.}) 8... exd4 9. cxd4 Bg4
{Anand uses an approach we are already familiar with. The game continued} 10.
Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nc3 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Qd7 {[%cal Gf6h5,Gd7h3] Black is ready to
exploit White's kingside weaknesses by playing Nf5 followed by Qh3 and
eventually f7-f5. Black's advantage is out of question.}) ({In two of his
games at the FIDE Candidates tournament, Anand gave preference to the more
positional} 7. h3 {White doesn't rush with the move d3-d4 and prefers first to
prevent his opponent from creating a pin along the h1-d1 diagonal. If Black
plays passively, White could play 8.d4 and after 8...exd4 9.cxd4 Bb6, he could
simply follow with Nc3 or Re1 since Bg4 is no longer possible. Given the fact
that White's light-squared bishop occupies the a4-e8 diagonal, Black couldn't
go for the "mysterious" Re8 which is familiar to us.   As you are going to see
on multiple occasions, in such situation almost always Black should go for the
typical knight transfer} Ne7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Gc7c6,Gd6d5] We are already familiar
with this idea. Black knight is heading to g6-square. As we know, now the
c7-pawn could participate in the fight for the centre. One of Black's main
ideas in such kind of positions is to carry out the typical c7-c6 followed by
d6-d5. That's why White should play very energetically.} 8. d4 Bb6 {This
position was reached in the game Anand - Karjakin played at the FIDE
Candidates 2016. At this point, Vishy went for} 9. Bd3 ({Similar to the game
is the continuation} 9. Re1 {when after} d5 10. Nxe5 Nxe4 11. Nd2 Nd6 {we
enter the same pawn structure.}) 9... d5 $1 {This modern approach to the
position is the most direct way to equalize. Black immediately challenges the
centre without waiting the development of his opponent's pieces.} 10. Nxe5 {
This nautural move turns out to be a novelty in the concrete situation. The
The critical position arises after the moves} ({More popular is} 10. Nbd2 {A
critical test for this line was the game Carlsen - Kramnik played in 2015.
It's interesting to see how the Wch managed to outpreare an outstanding
theoretician like Kramnik.   After} dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 exd4 {Carlsen
came up with an original idea.} 13. Qc2 {Of course, White should find a way to
complicate matters since positions with an isolated pawn don't promise much
here - it's extremely difficult to organize a kingside attack.  The game
continued} h6 14. a4 $1 {This is the point. White not only gains space on the
queenside but at the same time, he is playing against the restricted b6-bishop.
As we are going to see soon, different tactical ideas connected with a4-a5
advance are always in the air. Nevertheless, with a precise play, Black should
easily equalize.} c6 15. Rd1 Nd5 16. Nxd4 Re8 {Even though it seems that Black
managed to solve his immediate problems, Carlsen finds a way to put more
pressure.} 17. a5 Bxa5 18. Nf3 $1 {[%cal Gc3c4] Now White is threatening to
win a piece by means of c3-c4. Black's next move is forced} b5 ({A blunder
would have been} 18... Qc7 $4 {since White is winning a piece.} 19. Bxd5 cxd5
20. Qa4 {[%csl Ra5,Re8][%cal Ga4a5,Ga4e8]}) 19. Nd4 {And now Black could have
solved all the problems by playing the natural} Bb7) 10... Nxe4 11. Nd2 Nd6 {
[%cal Gf7f6,Gc8f5,Gd2b3,Gb3c5] We reach the sturcture which was covered in my
comments to the variation 5.Re1 Nd6 6.Nxe5 Be7 7.Bf1 Nf5.  However, here, we
have a better version for Black. He had already managed to play Nc6-e7,
removing his knight from the way of c7-pawn. That's why, Black has no problems
to fight for the centre by means of c7-c6 or even c7-c5. Moreover, the other
black knight occupied his best square - d6. If White doesn't achieve something
concrete, Black achieve a complete equality by following four simple steps:  1)
chase away white e5-knight by means of f7-f6  2) activate the dark-squared
bishop via c7-square after playing c7-c6  3) exchange light-squared bishops by
playing Bf5  4) play Ng6 and exchange heavy pieces along the open e-file  In
order to avoid that scenario, White should play extremely energetically.   The
game continued} 12. Nb3 {[%cal Gb3c5] The white knight is heading for c5. Here,
Black could have equalized by means of} f6 13. Nf3 Bf5 14. Nc5 {This is by far
the most ambitious continuation. White tries to make use of the weakened
e6-square and at the same time creates pressure against black b7-pawn. Black,
however, has enough resources to equalize. For example, the position arising
after} ({The natural} 14. Bf4 {leads to an easy equality after} Bxd3 15. Qxd3
Ng6) 14... Re8 15. Re1 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Ng6 {seems to be completely equal.}) ({
The modern grandmaster practice proved that the attempt to create a pin along
the h4-d8 diagonal by playing} 7. Bg5 {fails to achieve something special.
Black could follow with} h6 8. Bh4 g5 {The main line goes} 9. Bg3 ({The
sacrifice} 9. Nxg5 {doesn't seem to be completely correct.} {In my game
against Akopian played in 2006, I played} hxg5 {The game continued} 10. Bxg5
Kg7 11. Bxc6 ({In case of} 11. Qf3 {Black's best reaction is} Qe7 {[%cal Ge7e6]
followed by Qe6. Once our queen reaches the e6-square, we not only escape from
the unpleasant pin but at the same time, in case of necessity, the queens
could be exchanged via g4-square. For example, the game Dragomirescu -
Pashikian played in 2012, saw} 12. Nd2 a6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Qg3 Qe6 $1 {This
typical move could be played even here, since White has not a suitable
discovered check. After} 15. d4 Ba7 16. Bxf6+ Kxf6 17. Nf3 Qg4 18. dxe5+ Ke7 {
It's Black who has the advantage.}) 11... bxc6 12. d4 Bb6 13. a4 ({Despite the
fact that the move} 13. f4 {looks threatening, Black has nothing to worry
about. He should play} exd4 14. cxd4 ({Black is winning after} 14. e5 $2 dxe5
15. fxe5 dxc3+ 16. Kh1 Qxd1 17. Rxd1 cxb2 $19) 14... Qe8 $1 {White is a piece
down, his central pawns are vulnerable and he has no chance to organize a
kingside attack.}) 13... a5 14. Qf3 Qe7 15. Nd2 Qe6 {And White has run out of
attacking resources. I won the game on move 38.}) 9... Nh5 {We should always
keep an eye on the g3-bishop since White will be trying to activate it by
playing d3-d4.} 10. Nbd2 {This is the most popular move. Before starting
concrete actions in the centre, White wants to complete the development.} ({
The immediate} 10. d4 {is not particularly dangerous. Here, Black shouldn't be
afraid of sacrificing a pawn after} Bb6 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. dxe5 Nxg3 13. hxg3
dxe5 14. Nxe5 Ba6 {[%csl Ga6,Gb6][%cal Ga6f1,Gb6f2] The mighty pair of bishops
fully compensates the missing pawn. This position was reached in the game
Kasimdzhanov - Bok played in 2014. In this game, White played} 15. Qxd8 Raxd8
16. Re1 {but after} f5 {Black developed a strong initiative.}) 10... Qf6 $1 {
The queen belongs to f6 in this position. From here, it controls the important
squares d4 and f4.} 11. Kh1 {By playing this move, White wants to answer the
eventual Nxf3 by taking with his f-pawn, thus creating a dangerous opposition
between the f1-rook and black queen. One of White's main ideas in this
position is to play d3-d4. In this case, the move exd4 could be answered by
Nxd4, using the fact that black h5-knight is currently hanging. As Kramnik
recently proved, however, Black is just in time to transfer his c6-knight to
the kingside. In his recent game against the strong Cuban GM Lazaro Bruzon, he
played} Ne7 {The game continued} 12. d4 exd4 13. Nxd4 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gd1h5]}
({The move} 13. cxd4 {is actually loosing a pawn after} Bxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxg3+ 15.
fxg3 Qxd4) 13... Nf4 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ge7g6,Gd2b3] Black is going for a dark
square strategy. He wants to bring his e7-knight to e5 via g6-square.} 14. N4b3
Neg6 15. f3 a6 16. Nxc5 axb5 17. Ncb3 c5 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8a6,Gb5b4,Gg6e5]
Black's advantage is out of question. His knights are perfectly placed and he
his pawns controls a lot of important squares. Later on, he could further
activate his pieces by playing Ba6 followed by b5-b4. At the same time,
White's pieces are extremely passive. The g3-bishop is neutralized, it's not
clear how the queen will enter the game and there are no suitable outposts for
the knights. Furthermore, White has to reckon with the weakness of his light
squares (especially d3-square).}) ({White players who are not very ambitous
could give preference to the positional} 7. Re1 {The idea of this move is to
execute the typical d3-d4 advance with a tempo. That's why, here, we should
spend one more move before going for the typical Ne7-g6.} Bb6 {[%cal Gc6e7,
Ge7g6]} 8. h3 {This move seems to be necessary. Firstly, White need to prevent
his opponent from creating a pin along the h5-d1 diagonal.} ({In case of the
immediate} 8. d4 {Black reacts with the typical} exd4 9. cxd4 Bg4 {[%csl Rd4,
Re4,Rf3][%cal Gc6d4,Gh5d1] White has problems to defend his central pawns. As
always, he should part with his pair of bishops. Even in this case, however,
the centre will be under pressure.}) 8... Ne7 {[%cal Ge7g6] Now Black has
enough time to execute the desired transfer of his knight. In the game Antipov
- Alekseev, played in 2013, White went for a slow strategy which is quite a
characteristic for the Giuoco Piano.} 9. Ba4 {[%cal Ga4c2] Generally, this is
a useful move. The bishop is going to be transfererred to the c2-square. Also,
it's important to mention, that by white bishop is badly placed on b5 since in
a number of positions, Black wants to play c7-c6 followed by d6-d5.} ({Note
that the move} 9. d4 {is again well met by} d5 {entering the structure we are
familiar with.} ({Of course, there are is nothing wrong with the traditional} 
9... Ng6)) 9... Ng6 10. Nbd2 c6 {Black is going for a central activity. Now in
response of} 11. Nf1 {he carried out the typical} d5 {The position is
completely equal. Note that White couldn't win a pawn by means of} 12. exd5
Nxd5 13. Nxe5 {because of} Nxe5 14. Rxe5 Bxf2+ $1 {This tactical shot is
possible due to the unprotected position of white e5-rook. This is what
happened in the abovementionned game.}) 7... Ne7 {The credit for this idea
goes to Kramnik. As saw on a number of occasions, despite the fact that White
manages to occupy the centre, Black starts attacking his central pawns.} 8. d4
exd4 9. cxd4 Bb6 10. Re1 {This is the exact move order. In this position, the
importance of the control over the e4-square is crucial.} ({At first sight,
White could prevent his opponent from creating a pin by means of the simple} 
10. h3 {Black, however, has a powerful response at his disposal.} d5 $1 11. e5
Ne4 {White couldn't win the battle for the e4-square due to his vulnerable
d4-pawn. For example, after} 12. Qe2 Bf5 13. Bd3 {Black is just in time to
start putting pressure on d4.} Nc6 $1 {And it's obvious that White's opening
concept has failed.}) 10... Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 {We reached probably the most
important position of the entire variation. Both sides achieved their own -
White has a strong pawn centre while Black is ready to attack it. Black is
planning to put further pressure on white central pawns by playing moves like
a7-a6 followed by Re8 and Nc6 ( of course, different move orders are possible )
. On the other hand, White will be trying to make use of his spatial advantage.
In a number of positions, he challenges the coordination between black pieces
by starting an active play in the centre based on the e4-e5 advance. The
position is very complicated.  At this point, White has three major options -
12.Qb3 (we deal with it in the next game), 12.a3 and 12.a4.} 12. a4 {This move
is a novelty. By gaining space on the queenside, White starts playing against
opponent's dark-squared bishop - now black should reckon with the direct
threat a4-a5. On the other hand, with his last move, Anand weakens the
b4-square.} ({In this line of thoughts, it's interesting to consider the idea} 
12. a3 {which was introduced by the French top GM Vachier Lagrave in his game
against Sergey Karjakin played in 2015. White's main idea consists in covering
the b4-square which is important in a number of variations. In order to start
attacking white centre by Nc6 and Re8, Black should firstly remove opponent's
bishop from the a4-e8 diagonal.} a6 13. Bf1 {This is White's most natural
option. From f1, the bishop controls the queenside and at the same time, under
favourable circumstances, could be transferred to the h1-a8 diagonal after
g2-g4.} ({In two games, White insisted on keeping his bishop on the a4-e8
diagonal.} 13. Ba4 {The main drawback of this move is that now white queen
couldn't easily enter the game. In order to do so, White should eliminate the
pin along the h5-d1 diagonal by playing g2-g4. In the game Bok,B - Kovalenko,
I, played in 2015, Black came up with a very flexible approach.} Kh8 {[%csl
Gf6,Gg8][%cal Gd6d5] Black preapres the central d6-d5 break. With a king on h8,
the move e4-e5 could always be met by Nfg8. The following sequence seems
obvious.} 14. g4 Bg6 15. Bc2 d5 16. e5 Nfg8 17. Nb3 Nc6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gf7f6]
Another natural move. Now Black is ready to play Nge7 followed by f7-f6,
activating his pieces and eliminating White's spatial advantage.} 18. Bxg6 fxg6
19. Be3 h6 20. Kg2 Nge7 21. Qd3 Qd7 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gc6d8,Gd8e6] Black solved his
opening problems. Now he could consider further improving of the position of
his pieces by means of g6-g5 followed by the typical manoeuvre Nd8-e6.}) 13...
Re8 {Karjakin goes for the most precise move order.} ({The idea of White's 12.
a3 could be seen in the following variation.} 13... Nc6 14. e5 dxe5 15. dxe5
Nd7 16. Nc4 Bc5 {And here, since the pawn is on a3, White could go for b2-b4
followed by Bb2.}) {The game Lagrave - Karjakin continued} 14. e5 Nfd5 15. Nc4
Ba7 16. g4 Bg6 17. Bg5 {It seems that White has overtaken the initiative.
Nevertheless, his position is a little bit weakened and  the c4-knight is
unstable. Black makes use of these factors in order to gain space on the
queenside.} dxe5 18. dxe5 h6 19. Bh4 b5 20. Na5 Qc8 {[%cal Gc7c5] This is an
important preparatory move. Black wants to play c7-c5 without allowing the
manoeuvre Nb7-d6. After} 21. Rc1 c5 22. b4 c4 23. Nd4 Qc7 {[%cal Ga8d8]
followed by Rad8, Black obtained an excellent position. He has a defended
passed pawn and better coordinated pieces. Later on, Karjakin managed to win
the game.}) 12... a6 13. Bf1 Re8 {Of course, there are is nothing wrong with
this natural move. Topalov starts playing against opponents centre.} ({The
alternative} 13... Nc6 {also deserves serious attention.} 14. d5 ({The move} 
14. e5 {is no longer dangerous since after} dxe5 15. dxe5 Nd5 16. Nc4 {Black
just plays} Bc5 {Given the fact that White had already played a2-a4, he
couldn't bother the c5-bishop by means of b2-b4.}) 14... Ne5 {If White tries
to put pressure on b7 by playing} 15. a5 Ba7 16. Qb3 {Black managed to create
a well timed counterplay based on the attack against the e4-pawn. For instance,
after} Nxf3+ 17. Nxf3 Re8 {The position is roughly equal.}) 14. a5 Ba7 15. Qb3
{A multipurpose move. White not only eliminates the unpleasant pin but at the
same time he attacks the b7-pawn. Black should play very energetically if he
doesn't want to find himself in a difficult situation.} Nc6 $1 {Topalov
continues to play in an extremely precise way. He makes use of the major
drawback in White's concept - there is no suitable way in which the d4-pawn
could be defended. By advancing it, White will make possible the activation of
black dark-squared bishop. The following next moves are forced.} 16. d5 Nd4 17.
Nxd4 Bxd4 18. Qxb7 Nd7 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gd7c5] Black sacrificed a pawn in
order to overtake the initiative. Now he will be trying to make use of his
better developed pieces and the restricted mobility of white queen.} 19. Nc4 {
This move seems to be dubious since black minor pieces could become extremely
dangerous.} ({White could have gone for an original exchange sacrifice.} 19.
Ra3 Qh4 20. Rae3 {This position is highly complicated. White's pair of bishops
and Black's weaknesses on c7 and a6 compensate the missing exchange. The
position could be evaluated as balanced.}) 19... Nc5 20. Qc6 Nb3 $6 {Topalov
misses an excellent opportunity to take the advantage.} ({He should have played
} 20... Bxf2+ $1 {After the forced seqence} 21. Kxf2 Qh4+ 22. g3 Nxe4+ 23. Rxe4
Qxe4 24. Ne3 Qf3+ 25. Kg1 Qxg3+ 26. Ng2 Qxh3 27. Ra3 Qg4 28. Bf4 Qd1 {[%cal
Gh5e2] Black has an obvious advantage. Now he is threatening to win the game
by means of Be2.}) 21. Rb1 Nxc1 $6 ({Correct is} 21... Bg6 22. Bd3 f5 $1) 22.
Rbxc1 Rb8 23. Qxa6 Qh4 24. Rc2 Rxe4 25. Ne3 $1 {White has managed to
consolidate his position. Now the f2-pawn is well protected and White's
a5-passed pawn could be moved forward.} Qd8 26. Qc4 Bg6 27. Bd3 $1 Rf4 28. Bxg6
hxg6 29. g3 Re4 30. a6 ({Another strong option was} 30. Rd1 Qf6 31. Kg2 {White
is winning because of the threat 32.Ng4 followed by f2-f3.}) 30... Qe8 31. Rce2
Bb6 32. Qd3 Ra8 33. Kg2 (33. b4 $1 Kf8 34. Ng4 Rxe2 35. Rxe2 Qa4 36. b5 $18)
33... Qa4 34. b3 Rd4 35. bxa4 (35. Qc2 Qxa6 36. Nf5 Qxe2 37. Rxe2 gxf5 38. Qxf5
$16) 35... Rxd3 36. Nc4 Rxa6 37. a5 Bd4 $2 (37... Bc5 $1 $14) 38. Re8+ Kh7 39.
R1e7 Rc3 40. Nd2 $6 (40. Re4 $1 Bf6 41. Rf8 g5 42. Rxf7 Rd3 43. Re6 Kg6 44.
Rxc7 Rxd5 45. g4 $18) 40... Rc2 ({Black's last chance was} 40... f5 $1 41. h4
Bf6) 41. Ne4 f6 42. h4 Rxa5 43. Rf7 g5 44. h5 Rxf2+ 45. Nxf2 Ra2 46. Rff8 Rxf2+
47. Kh3 g4+ 48. Kxg4 f5+ 49. Rxf5 1-0

