{In this game, I examine White's most popular continuation in the 5.c3 line -
12.Qb3 instead of Anand's 12.a4. This move was tried by Fabiano Caruana in his
game against Anish Giri played in at the FIDE Candidates 2016. In my analysis
to this game, I prove that, with a precise play, Black has no problems to hold
the equality.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 {This is a
slightly different move order. As we have seen, in his game against Topalov,
Anand went for 5.0-0. In the vast majority of the cases, it's just a
transposition.  At this point, Black's most precise move order seems to be} O-O
{As the positions arising after 5...d6 6.d4 exd4 7.cxd4 Bb4+ 8.Kf1 are not so
clear, Black finishes the development without wasting time.} 6. O-O ({The
attempt to win a pawn by means of} 6. Bxc6 bxc6 7. Nxe5 {doesn't lead to an
advantage for White. Black's pair of bishops and better development fully
compensate White's extra pawn. Here, you should know that the best move is} d5
{This approach to the position is very logical - when you have a pair of
bishops, you should try to open up the position.   After} 8. d4 {, instead of
the regularly played 8...Bb6, I recommend quite a fresh idea} Qe8 {Black tries
to make use of the vulnerable position of white e5-knight. At the same time,
he is planning to follow with dxe4 on the next move. Later on, black
dark-squared bishop will go to the more active d6-square. This approach was
introduced by the strong French GM Laurent Fressinet in his game against Tairi.
The game continued} 9. O-O ({Too risky is} 9. exd5 {Here, instead of trying to
regain the material, Black should prevent White from castling by means of the
precise} Ba6 $1 {The game may continue} 10. dxc6 Bd6 {[%csl Re1] Despite the
fact that White has three extra pawns, he is struggling to equalize since his
king is under the fire of opponents pieces. Note that every position with
opposite coloured bishops is very difficult for White. A possible continuation
would be} 11. f4 Rd8 $1 {Another precise move. Black is planning to play Bxe5
followed by Nd5 and f7-f6, thus opening up the centre. The move 11...Rd8 is
desinged to protect the central d5-knight and to create an unpleasant
opposition along the d-file.} 12. Qf3 Nd5 $1 {[%cal Gd6e5] This is the point!
Now 13...Bxe5 followed by f7-f6 is comming. White couldn't take the knight
because after} 13. Qxd5 Bxe5 14. Qxe5 Qxc6 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gf8e8,Ge8e2,Ga6e2,
Ga8h1] his king is helpless.}) 9... dxe4 10. Nd2 Bd6 11. Ndc4 Be6 12. Re1 c5
13. Be3 Nd5 {With a very promising position for Black - white e5-knight is
unstable.}) 6... d6 {We entered the main line.} 7. Nbd2 Ne7 8. d4 exd4 9. cxd4
Bb6 10. Re1 Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 12. Qb3 {This is the most popular move in the
position. White removes his queen from the pin and intends to continue
developing his pieces. If he manages to finish the development without
conceding his centre, Black will face serious difficulties to equalize. That's
why he should play very energetically.} d5 13. e5 Nd7 {Black is ready to
attack White's centre by means of the typical f7-f6. It's important to point
out that if in response to f7-f6 White plays e5-e6, Black could create
pressure against the d4-pawn by executing the manouevre Nb8-c6 ( sometimes
this manoeuvre works even without the inclusion of the move f7-f6 and e5-e6).}
14. Qd1 $5 $146 {This is already a novelty. At first sight, the queen retreat
looks illogical - white f3-knight is pinned again. Nevertheless, now the pawn
structure is different. Later on, White will protect his d4-pawn by playing
Nb3 and will consider advancing his pawn majority on the kingside.  Up to this
game, White played the move Qd1 only after the inclusion of the move a2-a4 and
a7-a5 - 14.a4 a5 15.Qd1. It's difficult to say of the inclusion of these moves
is in his favor or not. It's true that in some cases White will be able to
bring his queenside rook into play by means of Ra3. Furthermore, under
favorable circumstances, he could make use of the weakened position of black
b6-bishop. On the other hand, Black will be trying to make use of the weakened
b4-square. Anyway, even in case of 14.a4 a5 15.Qd1, we will follow the
strategy chosen by Giri.} f6 15. e6 Nb8 16. Nb3 Qd6 17. g4 Bg6 18. Nh4 Nbc6 {
This is a solid positional approach - by developing his knight, Black
strengthens the pressure against white d4-pawn.} ({Interesting complications
arise after my idea} 18... Be4 $146 {In a suitable moment, Black is planning
to eliminate White's e6-pawn. I have analysed the following variation} 19. Nf5
Qxe6 20. f3 Nxf5 21. gxf5 Qd6 22. fxe4 Qg3+ 23. Kf1 Qxh3+ {Black's attack
compensates the missing piece. For example} 24. Kf2 Qh2+ 25. Ke3 a6 (25... c6
26. Be2 Re8 27. Rh1 Qg3+ 28. Kd2 Rxe4 29. Bf3 Rf4 30. Rf1 Na6 31. Kc3 Rxf5 32.
Qd3 Qg6) 26. Ba4 Qg3+ 27. Kd2 Ba7 {[%cal Gb7b5] White should do someting
urgent since b7-b5 is comming.} 28. Nc5 Bxc5 29. dxc5 Qf2+ 30. Re2 Qd4+ 31. Ke1
Qg1+ 32. Kd2 Qd4+ {With a prepetual.}) 19. Bxc6 Qxc6 20. Bd2 Bc2 21. Qe2 Bxb3
$6 {This move seems dubious to me. Even though Black's desire to win a pawn is
understandable, with his last move, he gives White the chance to create a
dangerous initiative.} ({More to the point would have been} 21... Qc4 {A
logical move the idea of which is to fight for the control of the weakened
light-squares. After an eventual exchange of the queens, Black will take the
control over the d5-square.} 22. Bc3 (22. Qxc4 dxc4 23. Nc5 Rfd8 {With an
advantage for Black.}) 22... Bxb3 23. axb3 Qxb3 {Black has an extra pawn but
White's compensation is based on his passed pawn on e6. The position remains
highly complicated.}) 22. axb3 Bxd4 23. Bb4 {White managed to overtake the
initiative. Since Black is forced to play 23...Bc5, there will be an annoying
pin along the c-file. In order to escape it, Black should give back his extra
pawn and enter a position with an inferior pawn structure.} Bc5 24. Rec1 b6 25.
Bxc5 bxc5 26. Ra6 Qb7 27. Rxc5 Rfe8 28. Qb5 $6 {The exchange of the queens is
premature.} ({Correct was} 28. b4 c6 29. Nf5 Qxb4 30. Nxe7+ Rxe7 31. Raxc6 {
when White's advantage is out of question.}) 28... Qxb5 29. Rxb5 d4 $1 {By
moving his passed pawn forward, Black tries to deflect white pieces from their
active positions.} 30. Nf5 Rad8 31. Rxa7 Nxf5 32. gxf5 d3 33. Ra1 g6 34. Rc5
Re7 35. Rd1 gxf5 36. Rc6 Rd4 37. Kg2 Kg7 38. Kf3 Kg6 39. Rc4 Rd5 40. Rc3 d2 41.
Re3 Rd6 42. Re2 {And the draw was agreed.} 1/2-1/2

[Event "FIDE Candidates 2014"]
[Site "Khanty-Mansiysk RUS"]
[Date "2014.03.18"]
[Round "5.3"]
[White "Andreikin, D."]
[Black "Anand, V."]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
