{This game marks the beginning of the part dedicated to 4.d3 followed by Bxc6.
Given the fact that recently this approach is highly popular, we should study
it very carefully.   The first game, I provide you with, features the somewhat
rare move 6.Be3. Here Black has two main options - 6...Bxe3 or 6...Bd6. In the
current game, Anand goes for the first option. According to my analysis,
despite the fact that Black parts with the bishop pair, he has no problems to
maintain the balance in this structure.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 {Nowadays, this move can be called the main line since it
arises in the vast majority of the top level games. The structure is typical
for the exchange variation of Ruy Lopez defence. I will try to explain the
plans for both sides.   White:   1. White has a better pawn structure, if he
manages to exchange all the pieces, the pawn endgame will be lost for Black;  
2. White should try to exchange the dark-squared bishops and then prepare
f2-f4;   3. In an appropriate moment he should try to open the centre with
d3-d4;   4. In some cases, he could play 0-0-0 and start a direct attack
against Black's king;   5. Generally, White tries to win space advantage on
the king side.   Black:   1.Black has two bishops and can easily develop his
pieces.   2.The main problem for Black is the passive knight on f6, so the
manoeuvre Nf6-d7-f8-e6 is very typical, other options is Nf6-d7-c5-e6.  
Another route for the knight is Nd7-b8-c6;   3. Black can play with 0-0 or
0-0-0, depending on the concrete situation.} 6. Be3 {An interesting idea which
is not very popular these days. White wants to exchange the dark-squared
bishops. In this case, Black couldn't enjoy his pair of bishops anymore.
Moreover, his remaining c8-bishop is rather passive due to the fact that it's
restricted by his own pawns. On the other hand, White's pawn structure will be
a little bit spoiled. Given the abovementionned consideration, we could draw
the concusion that the arising positions are rather complex.} Bxe3 {Another
option is 6...Bd6 which we will discuss in the next game.} 7. fxe3 Qe7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Qe1 {White has the idea to organize an attack against Black's king,
using the semi-open f-file.} Ne8 {Excellent idea! Anand transfers the knight
to d6 with thd aim to control the very important f5-square. Moreover, after
f7-f6 the e5-pawn will be well protected.} 10. Qc3 {Suddenly, White starts
playing on the other side of the board. In this concrete position, he is
planning Nbd2 followed by b2-b4 and a2-a4, thus gaining a considrable amount
of space on the queenside.} ({Another very interesting option is to start
playing on the king side.} 10. Qg3 f6 11. Nc3 Nd6 12. Nh4 Be6 {White has no
resources for a successful attack. For example:} 13. Rf2 b5 14. Raf1 a5 15. Nf5
(15. b3 a4 $1) 15... Nxf5 (15... Bxf5 16. exf5 Rfe8 17. e4 a4 $11) 16. exf5 Bd5
17. e4 Bf7 18. Qe3 a4 $15 {Black's position is a bit better, because of the
space advantage on the queen side. It is risky for White to try a massive
attack against Black's king. For instance after} 19. g4 b4 20. Ne2 Bxa2 21. g5
fxg5 22. Rg2 Kh8 23. Rxg5 Bg8 $19 {Black's king is safe. At the same time, the
a- pawn is very dangerous and might decide the game.}) 10... f6 11. b4 {This
is aimed against a5 and c5. Furthermore, White starts gaining space on the
kingside.} Nd6 12. a4 Bd7 13. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2b3,Gb3c5]} b6 {[%csl Ra4,Gc5]
[%cal Gb6c5,Ga7a5] Strong prophylactic move which is designed to prevent White
from executing the typical Nb3-c5. At the same time, Black intends to follow
with a7-a5, thus creating an weakness on a4.} 14. a5 {This is the only
reasonable way to parry Black's positional threat.} Kh8 {A useful prophylactic
move the idea of which is to avoid any checks on the a2-g8 diagonal.} 15. Ra2 (
15. d4 {One of the main White's ideas is to play d4 and to open the centre.}
exd4 16. exd4 Nxe4 17. Qe3 {White sacrifices a pawn, but has some hopes to use
the pin along the e-file.} Rfe8 18. Rfe1 Bf5 19. Qf4 Bg6 20. Nh4 f5 21. c3 Qd6
22. Nxg6+ Qxg6 23. Nxe4 fxe4 24. Qxc7 {White equalized the material and has
some space advantage on the queen side, but the strong e4-pawn gives Black at
least an equal play.} bxa5 25. Qxa5 (25. Rxa5 e3 26. Qg3 Qc2 {Black has enough
counterplay}) 25... e3 {The game is about equal. Black's pawns on a7 and c6
are weak, but the strong passed pawn on e3 and the threats Qc2 and Qd3 give
Black a level game.}) (15. Rfe1 Rae8 16. d4 g5 $1 {At first sight, it looks
like Black only created a weakness in his camp, but White can't make use of it.
Later on, Black will continue to develop his initiative on the king side.})
15... Rab8 16. axb6 axb6 17. Qa1 (17. Rfa1 Rfd8 18. Qb2 Be6 $11) (17. h3 Rfd8
18. Raa1 $11) 17... Nb7 18. Qc3 c5 19. bxc5 Nxc5 {Black does not have doubled
pawns anymore and his knight has an excellent square - c5 . White should play
precisely to maintain the balance here.} 20. Ra7 Rfc8 21. Rfa1 b5 22. d4 $6 {
Openning the game is in Black's favour because now the d7-bishop becomes
active.} (22. Qb4 Qd6) 22... exd4 23. exd4 Nxe4 24. Nxe4 Qxe4 25. Rxc7 Bf5 {
Anand overplayed his opponent in the middle game and now has better chances.}
26. Raa7 $1 h6 27. Qd2 (27. Qe1 $5 $11) 27... Rxc7 28. Rxc7 Bg4 29. Rc3 b4 30.
Re3 Qd5 31. h3 Bf5 32. Rb3 Qc4 33. Rb2 Be4 34. Kf2 Bxf3 35. Kxf3 Rb5 36. Qd3 $1
Qxd3+ (36... Qc6+ 37. Kf2 Rg5 38. g3 Qd6 $15) 37. cxd3 Kg8 38. d5 $1 Kf7 39.
Ke4 Ke7 40. Kd4 Kd6 41. Kc4 Rc5+ 42. Kd4 Rxd5+ 1/2-1/2

[Event "US Chess League KO 2014"]
[Site "ICC INT"]
