[BlackTeam "St Louis"]

{The present game shows that instead of exchanging the dark-squared bishops,
Black could meet the move 6.Be3 by means of 6...Bd6. In this line, Black wants
keep his pair of bishops, planning to play more complicated positions.  The
way in which Wesley So exploits the potential of his pair of bishops is quite
instructive.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Be3 Bd6
{Black decides to keep his pair of bishops even at a cost of one tempo. This
is the more ambitious approach to the position. Black's plan is to complete
the development and to try to open the game. Another plan is c6-c5, followed
by Nf6-Nd7-Nb8-Nc6-Nd4, gaining the control of the centre. The typical
Nf6-d7-f8-e6 is also possible.} 7. h3 O-O 8. O-O Re8 9. Nbd2 Nd7 {Wesley So is
one of the strongest players in the world and his style is very creative. He
allows White to play d3-d4 and hopes that the pair of bishops will be the most
important factor in the arising position. Another possible plan is c6-c5 and
as mentioned above (in the comments to move 6), the idea to transfer the
knight to d4 will give Black a level game.} 10. d4 exd4 11. Bxd4 Nf8 12. Re1 c5
13. Bc3 b5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7] Of course! Black light-squared bishop belongs to
the long diagonal. At the same time, Black seizes the chance to gain space on
the queenside.} 14. b3 Bb7 15. e5 {As we have pointed out on many occasions,
in the Berlin structures, playing e4-e5 includes some important drawbacks.
First of all, white e5-pawn restricts the activity of the c3-bishop. Moreover,
since white light-squared bishop is already exchange, Black could establish a
total domination of the light squares. That's what Wesley So does in the
current game.} Be7 16. Qe2 b4 17. Bb2 Ne6 18. Qe3 Qd5 $1 19. Qe4 a5 ({The
immediate exchange of the queens deserves serious attention.} 19... Qxe4 20.
Nxe4 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4]} 21. a4 c4 $1 {Typical motif - Black sacrifices a pawn
to create weaknesses in White's camp.} ({Another possible move is} 21... bxa3
22. Bxa3 a4 23. bxa4 Rxa4 24. Nfd2 Bc6 {Despite the doubled pawns, Black is
slightly better, due to his more active pieces and the pair of bishops.}) 22.
bxc4 Red8 $17 {All Black's pieces are active and White's pawns on the
queenside are very weak. Black is clearly better.}) 20. Qg4 Red8 (20... a4 {
was also an interesting idea.} 21. Ne4 axb3 22. cxb3 Kh8 23. Qf5 Rf8) 21. Ne4 (
{After} 21. a4 $1 {Black has a very interesting option} Ra6 {transferring the
rook to the kingside.} 22. Nc4 Nd4 {[%cal Ga6g6]} 23. Bxd4 Rg6 24. Ne3 Qc6 25.
Nf5 Bf8 26. Qf4 Qxf3 27. Qxf3 Bxf3 28. Nh4 Rc6 29. Bxc5 Rxc5 30. Nxf3 Rxc2 {
Black is much better due to the weak b3-pawn, his better minor pieces and the
chance to create a passed pawn on the queen side.}) 21... Kh8 22. Ng3 Bf8 23.
h4 a4 {Black definitely won the opening battle and has a comfortable position.
His main achievements are the battery along the long diagonal and the space
advantage on the queenside. White's pieces are tied to the defense of the
g2-pawn.} 24. Rab1 Qc6 (24... h6 $5 $17) 25. h5 Rd2 26. Qf5 Rd7 27. Rbd1 Rxd1
28. Rxd1 Kg8 29. Qg4 axb3 30. axb3 Ra2 31. Rb1 Qa6 32. Kh2 $4 {This move loses
immediately.} (32. Nf5 $8 {was the only chance to continue the game.} g6 33.
Nd2 Qa8 34. Ne3 Bh6 35. Ndc4 Bg5 $15 (35... Bxe3 36. Nxe3 Be4 $17)) 32... Qc6
$2 {Black missed an easy win.} (32... Bxf3 33. Qxf3 Rxb2 34. Rxb2 Qa1 $19 {And
White should resign}) 33. Nh4 Qd5 34. f4 Be7 35. Ngf5 $2 ({The only chance for
White was:} 35. Nf3 h6 36. Nf5 Kf8 37. Nxe7 Kxe7 38. f5 Qe4 $1 39. Qxe4 Bxe4
40. fxe6 Bxc2 41. Ra1 Rxb2 42. exf7 Bxb3 43. Ra7 Bxf7 44. Rxc7+ Ke8 45. Rxc5 b3
46. Rb5 Bc4 $17 {With a good chance for Black to convert his advantage.}) 35...
Bxh4 36. Nxh4 Qe4 {White's position is hopeless with weak c2, f4 and g2 pawns
and passive pieces on the queen side. The only active idea is f4-f5, which is
not possible at the moment.} 37. Nf5 Qxc2 38. Rd1 Qxg2+ {Black enters a
winning endgame. Other moves also win. For example:} (38... g6 39. hxg6 hxg6
40. Nh6+ Kg7 41. Bc1 Qxg2+ 42. Qxg2 Rxg2+ 43. Kh3 Kxh6 44. f5+ Ng5+ 45. Kh4
gxf5 $19 {with mate to follow.}) (38... Kf8 39. h6 gxh6 40. Nxh6 Qg6 41. Qxg6
hxg6 $19) 39. Qxg2 Bxg2 40. Rd8+ $2 {Strange mistake, but the position is
totally lost anyway.} (40. Kxg2 Rxb2+ 41. Kf3 Rxb3+ 42. Ke4 Kf8 $19 {with 3
pawns up}) 40... Nxd8 0-1

[Event "5th Zurich CC 2016"]
[Site "Zurich SUI"]
[Date "2016.02.14"]
[Round "3.1"]
[White "Nakamura, Hi"]
[Black "Kramnik, V."]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
