{In this game, I bring to your attention a variation which became very popular
recently - 6.Nbd2. This move tends to be rather flexbile since White could go
either Nc4 or Nb3. Generally speaking, in this line, White often obtains a
pair of bishops. Nevertheless, in order to exchange one of the opponent's
bishops, he should spend some valuable time. Black makes use of it to activate
his minor pieces. I am convinced that the arising positions are pretty much
level.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 {A
modern line which recently became very popular at the highest level.} Be6 {I
decide to follow Kramnik's approach which is usually a very good idea in
Berlin defence. With his last move, Black not only takes under control the
important c4-square, but at the same time, he could proceed with Nd7 without
closing the way of his light-squared bishop.} 7. O-O (7. Nxe5 $4 {Of course
the pawn is untouchable since Black wins a piece by means of} Qd4) 7... Nd7 8.
Nb3 Bb6 9. Ng5 Bxb3 10. axb3 {White completes his mission - he forced Black to
part with his bishop player and took the control over the semi-open a-file.
Nevertheless, White has doubled pawns on the b-file and will need to spend
some more tempos on bringing his knight home.} f6 11. Nf3 Nc5 {Kramnik
deviates from his own game.} (11... Nf8 {Black's idea is to put the knight on
e6 and to take the control over the important squares d4 and f4. Also, Black
does not hurry to castle and keeps both options available. After castling long,
he could organize an attack on the kingside. White's main plan in this
position is to execute the manoeuvre Nf3-d2-c4 (or even Nh4) followed by Kh1,
f4 or g3 and f4.} 12. Nh4 (12. Nd2 Ne6 (12... Qd7 {It is better to start with
this move. Now Qh5 can be met with Qf7.} 13. Qh5+ Qf7) 13. Qh5+ g6 14. Qd1 Bc5
15. Nc4 b5 {Kramnik made a strange mistake for his level. Now Black's queen
side is weak.} 16. Na5 Qd7 17. Be3 Bb6 18. b4 O-O 19. Qd2 f5 20. exf5 gxf5 21.
Qc3 {And White won a wonderful game. 1-0 (33) Yu,Y (2705) -Kramnik,V (2760)
Doha 2014}) 12... Qd7 13. g3 Ne6 14. Kg2 O-O-O 15. Be3 Kb8 16. Bxb6 cxb6 $15 {
Now, Black's king is well protected by his four pawns and White cannot
organize any direct attack.} 17. f4 exf4 18. gxf4 g6 19. f5 Nd4 $17 {White's
problem is the weak king on g2. Any eventual oppening of the position will be
detrimental for White. 0-1 (40) Spraggett, K-Fressinet,L/Linares ESP 2014/The
Week in Chess 1035}) 12. Nd2 $146 O-O 13. Nc4 Ne6 14. Kh1 {So far, White plays
logically. Everything is ready for f2-f4.} Qd7 (14... Qe7 {Another option:} 15.
g3 Rad8 16. Be3 Kh8 (16... Bxe3 {is not a very good idea here, because it
gives White an easy game.} 17. Nxe3 a6 18. f4 exf4 19. gxf4 $14 {White has
better pawn structure and some chances to organize an attack along the g-file.}
) 17. f4 exf4 18. gxf4 f5 $1 {Very important move. Black replies to f4 with f5.
The e6-knight is perfectly placed and White's central pawns are blocked.}) 15.
Qg4 (15. f4 $5 exf4 16. Bxf4 {Instructive moment! For White is good to
exchange his bishop for Black's knight. Then, Black's bishop can be very
passive and without objects to attack. Additionally, White has the opportunity
to triple on the f-file.} f5 $1 {Very strong move.} 17. Nxb6 cxb6 18. Be3 fxe4
19. dxe4 {with equal game.}) 15... Rad8 16. Be3 Bd4 17. Bxd4 Nxd4 18. Qxd7 {
This leads to an equal endgame.} (18. Qd1 {was more ambitious} a6 19. Ne3 {
With a long approximately equal game.} (19. f4 {also does not lead to advantage
} exf4 20. Rxf4 c5 21. Ne3 $11)) 18... Rxd7 19. Rxa7 ({Possible was} 19. Ne3 a6
20. g3 {With the idea f2-f4.}) 19... Nxc2 20. Rxb7 Rxd3 21. h4 Nd4 22. b4 (22.
Rxc7 Rf7 23. Rc8+ Rf8 24. Rc7 Rf7 $11 {was the logical end of the game}) 22...
Ne6 23. Rc1 Ra8 24. b5 cxb5 25. Rxb5 Rad8 26. f3 h5 27. Kh2 Nf4 28. Rc5 R8d7
29. Na3 $2 {This move is a big mistake, now White loses the g2-pawn and his
position is hopeless.} Rd2 30. R1c2 Nxg2 31. Rxc7 Ne3+ 32. Rxd2 Rxd2+ 33. Kh3
Rf2 34. Kg3 Rxb2 35. Rc1 f5 $6 ({Simpler was} 35... Rg2+ 36. Kh3 Ra2 37. Rc3
Ng2 $19 {The position is easily winning for Black with his pawn up, more
active pieces and mating attack. Both players were in time trouble so this is
the only reason why Kramnik missed the chance to win the game.}) 36. Nc4 f4+
37. Kh3 Rf2 38. Nxe5 Nf1 39. Rxf1 Rxf1 40. Kg2 Ra1 41. Ng6 Ra2+ 42. Kg1 Ra1+
43. Kg2 Ra2+ 44. Kg1 Kf7 ({The only way which led to a win was:} 44... Ra7 $3
45. Nxf4 Rf7 46. Nxh5 g6 47. Ng3 Rxf3 48. Kg2 Rf4 49. Kh3 Kf7 $19 {and White
is in zugzwang.}) 45. Nxf4 g6 46. Ng2 Kf6 47. Kh2 Ke5 48. Kg3 {White build a
fortress. The position is a draw.} Ra1 49. Nf4 Kd4 50. Kg2 Ra2+ 51. Kg3 Ra1 52.
Kg2 Ra8 53. Kf2 Ra6 54. Ne2+ Ke5 55. Kg3 Rf6 56. Kf2 Rf8 57. Kg3 Rf7 58. Kf2
Ra7 59. Kg3 Ra8 60. Nf4 Rg8 61. Ne2 g5 62. hxg5 Rxg5+ 63. Kh4 Rg2 64. Ng3 Rh2+
65. Kg5 h4 66. f4+ Ke6 67. Nf5 h3 68. Kg4 Rh1 69. Ng3 Rh2 70. e5 Rf2 71. Ne4
Rg2+ 72. Kxh3 1/2-1/2

[Event "London "]
[Site "London"]
[Date "2011.12.11"]
[Round "8"]
[White "Mc Shane, Luke"]
[Black "Kramnik, V."]
[Result "0-1"]
