{The main object of the current game is the rare 6.b3. In 2011, this approach
was tested by the British GM Luke Mc Shane in his game against Vladimir
Kramnik. I think that Kramnik's opening concept was very solid. He exchanged
his passive light-squared bishop for the opponent's f3-knight and later
neutralized white dark-squared bishop by means of Nd7 followed by f7-f6. This
game proves Black can even take the advantage in this variation.} 1. e4 e5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gb1d2,Gd2c4] This
move is very rarely played in the tournament practice. White delays castling.
Firstly, he wants to develop his pieces in the following way Bb2, Nd2-c4 and
then to decide where to castle.} Bg4 {Black develops logically. At an
appropriate moment, the bishop can be exchanged for the knight. The other
option is to defend the e5 pawn with Nd7 and f6.} 7. Nbd2 ({In case of} 7. h3
$6 {Black has a powerful response} Qd4 $3 {Very beautiful move which leads by
force to a better endgame for Black.} 8. Nxd4 Bxd1 9. c3 Bh5 10. Nf3 Bxf3 11.
gxf3 O-O-O 12. Ke2 Nh5 {[%cal Gh8f8,Gf7f5] Black takes under control the
important f4-square and prepares Rhf8 and f5. White will be struggling a lot
for a draw. Another idea is to double the rooks on the d-file by Rd7 and Rhd8
and to put pressure on the weak d3-pawn.}) 7... Nd7 8. Bb2 f6 {Black
successfully defended the e-pawn and now he should choose his plan. One is to
transfer the knight to e6 and to castle on the kingside and another one is to
play Qe7, make 0-0-0 and start a direct attack against White's king by pushing
h and g pawns.} 9. Nf1 Nf8 ({Kramnik could have taken advantage of White's
passive play by choosing the following variation:} 9... Qe7 10. Ne3 Be6 11. O-O
O-O-O {Black is ready to push h and g pawns further.}) 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Ne6
{As we already know, e6-square is the best for the knight.} 12. Ne3 Qd7 13. h4
a5 (13... O-O-O {There is nothing wrong to play with long castle} 14. O-O-O Kb8
15. Kb1 $15) 14. a4 O-O 15. h5 (15. O-O Bd4 16. Bxd4 Nxd4 17. Qd1 Rad8 {Black
has a good position mainly because of his wonderful d4-knight.}) 15... Bxe3 16.
Qxe3 (16. fxe3 h6 17. Qf5 Qe7 {We can evaluate this position as slightly
better for Black. His king is completely safe and he can try to gain some
space on the kingside by playing c6-c5, c7-c6 and b7-b5.}) 16... c5 {Kramnik
plays in a classical style, he puts his pawns on the same colour as his
opponent's bishop, takes the control over the d4-square and prepares an attack
against White's king.} 17. Qh3 Qc6 18. O-O Nf4 19. Qh2 Qe8 20. h6 g5 21. g3 Ne6
22. f4 $1 {A wonderful idea by White - he sacrifices a pawn and later an
exchange with the idea to open his bishop and the g-file.} gxf4 23. gxf4 Nxf4
24. Rxf4 exf4 25. Kf2 ({The alternative was:} 25. Qxf4 Ra6 26. Kf2 f5 27. exf5
Qf7 28. Rg1+ Rg6 29. f6 Re8 {Black keeps his material advantage and has better
chances. Nevertheless, White has some compensation due to weak Black's pawns.}
30. Rg5 Kf8 31. Be5) 25... Rf7 26. Qh5 $6 ({Better was} 26. Qxf4 Qe6 27. Rg1+
Kf8 28. Rg7 Rc8 29. Rxf7+ Kxf7 30. Qg3 Rg8 31. Qxc7+ Qe7 {With nearly equal
game due to unsafe position of Black's king and many weaknesses in Black's
camp.}) 26... Qe6 (26... b6 27. Rg1+ Kf8 28. Qg4 Ke7 29. Qxf4 Qc6 $15 30. Rg7
Raf8 31. Qf5 $11) 27. Qxc5 Kh8 28. Qc4 (28. Qd5 $1 Qxd5 29. exd5 Re8 30. Bd4
$11) 28... Re8 29. Rh1 Qd7 30. Qb5 Re6 31. Qxd7 ({Stronger was:} 31. Kf3 $1 Qc6
32. Qxc6 Rxc6 33. Rh2 $14) 31... Rxd7 32. Rg1 Rc6 33. Kf3 Rd8 34. Rg5 Rf8 35.
Rg2 (35. Rxa5 Kg8 36. c4 Rb6 37. Rb5 Rxb5 38. cxb5 Kf7 39. Kxf4 Rg8 40. Bc3 {
With chances for a draw.}) 35... Rg8 36. Rh2 Rg1 37. d4 $2 (37. Kxf4 Kg8 {
Black is much better, but fight continues.}) 37... Rf1+ 38. Kg4 f3 39. d5 Rd6
40. c4 Kg8 41. c5 f5+ {White resigns because of the following variation:} 42.
Kxf5 Rg6 43. Be5 Rg2 44. Rh3 f2 45. Rg3+ Rxg3 46. Bxg3 Rh1 47. Bxf2 Rf1 $19 0-1

