1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. h3 {This move is
played with the idea to take the g4-square under control. White delays the
castle and intends to complete the development with Be3, Nbd2 and then 0-0.
Afterwards, he has to choose between two plans: to play d3-d4 immediately or
after the inclusion of the move c3. or to consider playing on the queenside by
Nc4, a2-a3 followed by b2-b4.} Nd7 7. Be3 Bd6 {Black keeps the pair of bishops
since in this way, he could enter an open position with confidence.
Additionaly, by playing 7...Bd6, he protects the e5 -  pawn in a better way.
Now Black is ready to finish the development by 0-0 and Re8. The c8-bishop
could take part in the game after b6, Bb7 or Ba6.} 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. O-O Re8 {We
reached the main position of this variation. It's important to point out that
this position could be reached via different move orders: 6. Be3 Bd6 7.h3 0-0
8.0-0 Re8 9.Nbd2 Nd7 like in a game Becera Rivero-Wesley So. Also after the
moves 6.0-0 Nd7.} 10. Nc4 {[%cal Gd3d4] The knight obtained an optimal
position. The idea is to open the position with d3-d4. Another possible plan
for White is Nfd2 with the idea to prepare f2-f4 and to transfer the queen to
h5.} (10. d4 {This move was analyzed in the game Becera-So. The pair of
bishops are very powerful in this semi-open position.}) (10. c3 {This move is
preparing d4. The idea is to answer exd4 by cxd4 and to keep a strong pawn
centre, that will limit the activity of black pieces. This move is covered  
in the game Sevian-Le Quang Liem.}) 10... Nf8 11. d4 (11. c3 Ng6 12. Qc2 {This
is a possible continuation. I propose here the following variation:} Qe7 13. b4
b6 14. a4 Be6 15. Nxd6 cxd6 16. a5 b5 $11 {With an equal position. Black has
the idea f7-f5 with counterplay along the f-file.}) 11... exd4 12. Qxd4 c5 13.
Qd3 b6 {We already mentioned this idea. Black's c8-bishop is going to an
active position. The position already seems level to me.} 14. Nxd6 {White
decided to exchange some material and to enter an equal endgame.} ({To a more
complicated game leads} 14. Nfd2 Bb7 15. f4 Qh4 16. Rae1 Rad8 17. Qe2 Ng6 {
Black's pieces are very active and White has no real chance to organize an
attack. I prefer Black here.}) 14... Qxd6 15. Qxd6 cxd6 16. Rfd1 Bb7 17. Rxd6
Bxe4 18. Ne1 {A precise move that keeps the balance.} Rad8 19. Rad1 Ne6 20.
Rxd8 Rxd8 21. Rxd8+ Nxd8 22. f3 Bd5 23. a3 {The endgame is absolutely equal,
after 20 not so necessary moves the game ended in a draw.} Nc6 24. Kf2 f6 25.
Nd3 Kf8 26. Ke2 Ke7 27. Kd2 Kd7 28. Nf4 Bf7 29. b3 Ne7 30. h4 Nd5 31. Nxd5 Bxd5
32. Bf4 Kc6 33. Bg3 Bf7 34. Bf4 Bg6 35. Bg3 Bf7 36. Bb8 a6 37. Bf4 Bg6 38. Bg3
Bh5 39. Bf2 Bf7 40. Bg3 Bg6 1/2-1/2

[Event "SPICE Cup Open 2015"]
