1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. h3 Nd7 7. Be3 Bd6 8.
O-O O-O 9. Nbd2 Re8 10. c3 {Multi-purpose move. White plans to play d3-d4 and
to answer exd4 by cxd4. Also, White can prepare d4 break by playing Qc2, Rad1,
Rae1 before opening the game.} b6 {Our idea here is to activate the bishop on
b7, thus keeping an eye on e4, which will be weak after the eventual d3-d4.}
11. Qc2 Bb7 12. Rad1 c5 13. Rfe1 Qe7 14. Nf1 ({Better was the standard:} 14.
Nc4 Nf8 {With an approximately equal position with chances for both sides.})
14... Nf8 15. Ng3 g6 16. Bh6 Ne6 17. Qc1 Rad8 18. a3 a5 19. d4 $2 {This was a
wrong moment to play d3-d4. All Black's pieces are very well centralized and
the strength of the pair of bishops becomes a significant factor in the
arising position. Better for White was to continue with the waiting strategy
by playing:} (19. Nf1 f6 20. Ne3 Qf7 {Even here I prefer Black's position.})
19... cxd4 20. cxd4 Nxd4 21. Nxd4 exd4 22. Rxd4 Bxg3 $1 {Well calculated
positional decision. Black gives his dark-squared bishops and loses control of
the dark squares but wins a pawn and enters a winning endgame. This is one of
the advantages of the pair of bishops - you can always exchange one of them in
an appropriate moment.} ({Not so concrete, but also not bad was:} 22... c5 23.
Rd2 Be5 24. Rxd8 Rxd8 25. Bg5 f6 26. Bf4 Rd4 $15 {With better chances for
Black.}) 23. Rxd8 Bxf2+ 24. Kxf2 Qxd8 25. Kg1 Qd4+ 26. Kh2 c5 27. Qf4 Bxe4 {
Black is two pawns up. Despite the fact that the opposite coloured bishops and
the pin along the e-file make some technical difficulties, the position is
winning and Le Quang Liem confidently converts his advantage.} 28. Re2 Qe5 29.
Qxe5 Rxe5 30. Rd2 Rd5 31. Rxd5 Bxd5 32. Bg5 a4 33. Bd8 b5 34. Be7 c4 35. Bf6 h6
