1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 ({In this game I
will bring to your attention the variation that appeares after} 6. O-O {Now
our main line with Be6 is no longer possible. Black has a choice here.} Bg4 $5
{is very interesting} (6... O-O {My choice is to show you this move here,
because you can also use it as a backup repertoire after 6.Nd2}) 7. h3 Bh5 8.
g4 Nxg4 {And Black has good compensation for the sacrificed piece.}) 6... O-O
7. Nc4 (7. Qe2 {This is a modern line which Fabiano Caruana used to beat
Nakamura at the Candidates Tournament. White's idea is after Nc4 and Bd2 to
castle long and to start a kingside attack with g2-g4, h2-h4 and g4-g5.} Re8 8.
Nc4 Nd7 9. Bd2 Bd6 {We reach one of the most important positions in 6.Bxc6
line.} 10. O-O-O {A new try from Fabiano} (10. h4 {Was used by Caruana before
and also by Wei Yi who won a very beautiful game against David Navara after:}
c5 $6 {This the move is not so bad, but it is connected with a wrong plan to
transfer the knight from b8-c6 to d4. Instead of wasting a valuable time, it's
better to transfer the knight as soon as possible to the e6 - square.} (10...
Nf8 $1 {Karjakin's approach} 11. h5 Ne6) 11. h5 h6 12. O-O-O Nb8 13. Rdg1 Nc6 {
White's attack is very fast.} 14. g4 f6 15. g5 $1 {White sacrifices a piece
and obtaines a winning attack.} fxg5 16. Nxg5 Nd4 17. Qd1 hxg5 18. Bxg5 Be7 19.
Be3 {and Wei Yi soon won. Wei Yi - Navara Wijk an Zee 2016}) 10... b5 {Right
decision, Black should try to organize some counter play as soon as possible.}
11. Ne3 a5 12. Nf5 a4 13. Bg5 {The idea of this move is to provoke f6 and then
to start a direct attack with g4-g5.} f6 (13... Nf6 $6 14. g4 Be6 15. Kb1 b4
16. d4 {The position is far from clear, but looks better for White.}) 14. Be3
Nc5 15. g4 Be6 16. Kb1 b4 17. g5 {Until now both players played logically, but
now Hikaru made a mistake.} b3 $2 ({Black's best continuation is} 17... a3 $1 {
weakening the c3 - square. The game may continue} 18. b3 Bxf5 19. exf5 e4 {
Openning up the position. The game remains complicated but my analyses show
that Black has equal chances. For example:} 20. d4 (20. dxe4 Nxe4 21. Qc4+ Kh8
22. Rdg1 (22. Bd4 {looks dangerous, but after:} Ra5 23. gxf6 gxf6 24. Rhe1 Rxf5
25. Qxc6 Qe7 26. Nh4 Re5 $11 {Black should hold.}) 22... Ra5 $1 $15 {This rook
lift gives Black better chances.}) (20. Nd4 exd3 21. cxd3 fxg5 22. Qg4 Bf4 $11)
20... exf3 21. Qc4+ Ne6 22. fxe6 Qe7 23. h4 Qxe6 24. Qxc6 Qf5 $11) 18. Rhg1
bxa2+ 19. Ka1 Bxf5 20. exf5 a3 21. b3 {Black has no attack now. White's
initiative on the kingside looks very dangerous. 1-0 (33) Caruana,F (2794)
-Nakamura,H (2790) Moscow 2016}) 7... Nd7 8. Be3 Bd6 9. O-O Re8 {This is the
key position for the variation and can be reached by the following move order:
6.0-0 Nd7 7.Be3 Bd6 8.Nbd2 0-0 9.Nc4 Re8. It is quite similar to 6.h3
variation. The difference is that White has played Nc4 instead of h3 which
looks more active.} 10. d4 {White is trying to use his lead in development in
order to make d6-pawn an object of attack after the exchange.} exd4 11. Nxd6
cxd6 12. Qxd4 Qf6 $1 {Probably the best decision. Black exchanges the queens
and attacks the e4 - pawn. His only problem remains the undeveloped queenside.}
({In practice, many times was tried} 12... Ne5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15.
Rfd1 $14 {With a slight long term advantage for White.}) 13. Nd2 Qxd4 (13...
Ne5 {equalizes very easy} 14. Qc3 c5 15. Rfe1 Bd7 16. Rad1 Bc6 $11) 14. Bxd4 c5
15. Be3 b6 16. Nc4 {Forcing multiple exchanges. The arising endgame rook +
bishop vs rook + knight looks slightly better for White, but with a precise
play Black levels the game.} ({An interesting try was:} 16. Rfd1 Ne5 17. Bf4
Bb7 18. a4 d5 19. exd5 Bxd5 20. a5 b5 21. a6 $1 $14) 16... Ba6 17. Nxd6 Bxf1
18. Nxe8 Rxe8 19. Kxf1 Rxe4 20. Rd1 Re7 {White is slightly better because in
this position, the bishop is more useful than the knight, but there is not so
much material and White can't penetrate through d-file.} 21. a4 (21. b3 f6 22.
Bf4 Kf7 23. Bd6 Re8 $11) 21... f6 22. a5 Ne5 $1 23. axb6 axb6 24. Bf4 Kf7 25.
Bxe5 Rxe5 26. Rd7+ Re7 27. Rd6 Re6 28. Rd7+ Re7 29. Rd6 Re6 30. Rd7+ Re7
1/2-1/2

